# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: national-health-service
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 5 July 1945.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the ongoing Second World War still fresh in the minds of voters, the opposition Labour Party led by Clement Attlee won a landslide victory with a majority of 146 seats, defeating the incumbent Conservative-led government under Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result reflected widespread public concern about the future direction of the United Kingdom in the post-war period.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election's campaigning was focused on leadership of the country and its postwar future.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Opinion polls when the election was called showed strong approval ratings for Churchill, but Labour had held a lead in voting intention polls since 1943.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour won a landslide victory, gaining 239 seats for a total majority of 146 with 49.7% of the popular vote, allowing Attlee to become prime minister.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The party also won two seats in a walkover, the last time any seat in the House of Commons went uncontested in a general election.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This was Labour's first outright majority and enabled Attlee to begin implementing the party's post-war reforms.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result was a major shock for the Conservatives, who lost 189 seats despite winning 36.2% of the vote, having campaigned on the assumption that Churchill's wartime leadership would secure victory.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party suffered a net loss of nine seats and its leader Archibald Sinclair lost his seat, while the Liberal National Party lost 22 seats, including that of its leader Ernest Brown.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A total of 324 new MPs entered the House of Commons, a record that stood until 2024.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Additionally, the beginning of the Attlee ministry paralleled the beginning of the Truman administration in the United States.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The 11.7% swing from the Conservatives to an opposition party is the largest since the Acts of Union 1800; the Conservative loss of the vote exceeded that of the 1906 Liberal landslide ousting of a Conservative administration.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the first election since 1906 in which the Conservatives did not win a plurality (relative majority) of the popular vote.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill remained actively involved in politics and returned as prime minister after leading his party into the 1951 general election.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberal National Party the election was their last as a distinct party, as they merged with the Conservatives in 1947 (although they operated as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968) while Ernest Brown resigned from politics in the aftermath of the election.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Held less than two months following VE Day, this was the first general election since 1935, as general elections had been suspended by Parliament during the Second World War.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Clement Attlee, the leader of the Labour Party, refused Winston Churchill's offer of continuing the wartime coalition until the Allied defeat of Japan.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] On 15 June, King George VI dissolved Parliament, which had been sitting for nearly ten years without an election.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour manifesto, *Let Us Face the Future*, included promises of nationalisation, economic planning, full employment, a National Health Service, and a system of social security.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The manifesto proved popular with the electorate, selling one and a half million copies.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's Declaration to the Voters*, on the other hand, included progressive ideas on key social issues but was relatively vague on the idea of postwar economic control, and the party was associated with high levels of unemployment in the 1930s.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It failed to convince voters that it could effectively deal with unemployment in a postwar Britain.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In May 1945, when the war in Europe ended, Churchill's approval ratings stood at 83%, but the Labour Party had held an 18% poll lead as of February 1945.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The polls for some seats were delayed until 12 July and in Nelson and Colne until 19 July because of local wakes weeks.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The results were counted and declared on 26 July to allow time to transport the votes of those serving overseas.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Victory over Japan Day ensued on 15 August.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The caretaker government, led by Churchill, was heavily defeated.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party led by Attlee won a landslide victory and gained a majority of 146 seats.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the first election in which Labour gained a majority of seats and the first in which it won a relative majority (plurality) of votes.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a disaster for the Liberal Party, which lost all of its urban seats, and marked its transition from being a party of government to a party of the political fringe.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Its leader, Archibald Sinclair, lost his rural seat of Caithness and Sutherland.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] That was the last general election until 2019 in which a major party leader lost their seat, but Sinclair lost only by six votes in a very tight three-way contest.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal National Party fared even worse by losing two-thirds of its seats and falling behind the Liberals in seat count for the first time since the parties split in 1931.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the final election that the Liberal Nationals fought as an autonomous party, as they merged with the Conservative Party two years later although they continued to exist as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future prominent figures who entered Parliament included Harold Wilson, James Callaghan, Barbara Castle, Michael Foot and Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Conservative Prime Minister Harold Macmillan lost his seat, but he returned to Parliament at a by-election later that year.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The greatest factor in Labour's dramatic win appeared to be its policy of social reform.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In one opinion poll, 41% of respondents considered housing to be the most important issue that faced the country, 15% stated the Labour policy of full employment, 7% mentioned social security, 6% nationalisation, and just 5% international security, which was emphasised by the Conservatives.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Beveridge Report, published in 1942, proposed the creation of a welfare state.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It called for a dramatic turn in British social policy, with provision for nationalised healthcare, expansion of state-funded education, National Insurance and a new housing policy.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The report was extremely popular, and copies of its findings were widely purchased, turning it into a best-seller.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party adopted the report eagerly, and the Conservatives (including Churchill, who did not regard the reforms as socialist) accepted many of the principles of the report, but claimed that they were not affordable.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour offered a new comprehensive welfare policy, reflecting a consensus that social changes were needed.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were not willing to make the same changes that Labour proposed, and appeared out of step with public opinion.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour played to the concept of "winning the peace" that would follow the war.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Possibly for that reason, there was especially strong support for Labour in the armed services, which feared the unemployment and homelessness to which the soldiers of the First World War had returned.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It has been claimed that the left-wing bias of teachers in the armed services was a contributing factor, but that argument has generally not carried much weight, and the failure of the Conservative governments in the 1920s to deliver a "land fit for heroes" was likely more important.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had also been given during the war the opportunity to display to the electorate its domestic competence in government, under men such as Attlee as Deputy Prime Minister, Herbert Morrison at the Home Office and Ernest Bevin at the Ministry of Labour.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The differing wartime strategies of the two parties likewise gave Labour an advantage.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour continued to attack prewar Conservative governments for their inactivity in tackling Hitler, reviving the economy and rearming Britain, but Churchill was less interested in furthering his party, much to the chagrin of many of its members and MPs.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Though voters respected and liked Churchill's wartime record, they were more distrustful of the Conservative Party's domestic and foreign policy record in the late 1930s.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill and the Conservatives are also generally considered to have run a poor campaign in comparison to Labour.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's personal popularity remained high; hence, the Conservatives were confident of victory and based much of their election campaign on that, rather than proposing new programmes.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] However, people distinguished between Churchill and his party, a contrast that Labour repeatedly emphasised throughout the campaign.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Voters also harboured doubts over Churchill's ability to lead the country on the domestic front.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The writer and soldier Anthony Burgess remarked that Churchill, who then often wore a colonel's uniform, was not nearly as popular with soldiers at the front as with officers and civilians.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Burgess noted that Churchill often smoked cigars in front of soldiers who had not had a decent cigarette in days.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In addition to the poor Conservative general election strategy, Churchill went so far as to accuse Attlee of seeking to behave as a dictator, despite Attlee's service as part of Churchill's war cabinet.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In the most famous incident of the campaign, Churchill's first election broadcast on 4 June backfired dramatically and memorably.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Denouncing his former coalition partners, he declared that Labour "would have to fall back on some form of a Gestapo" to impose socialism on Britain.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Attlee responded the next night by ironically thanking the prime minister for demonstrating to the people the difference between "Churchill the great wartime leader" and "Churchill the peacetime politician" and argued the case for public control of industry.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Another blow to the Conservative campaign was the memory of the 1930s policy of appeasement, conducted by Churchill's Conservative predecessors, Neville Chamberlain and Stanley Baldwin, that had been widely discredited for allowing Adolf Hitler's Germany to become too powerful.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had strongly advocated appeasement until 1938, but the interwar period had been dominated by Conservatives.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the exception of two brief minority Labour governments in 1924 and 1929–1931, the Conservatives had been in power for all of the interwar period.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, the Conservatives were generally blamed for the era's mistakes: appeasement, inflation and the unemployment of the Great Depression.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Many voters felt that although the First World War had been won, the peace that followed had been lost.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] All comparisons are with the winning party in the 1935 election; the aim is to provide a comparison with the previous general election.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This list includes seats where the incumbent was standing down and therefore there was no possibility of a particular person being defeated.
[src:national-health-service/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Polls showed a lead for Labour since 1943, except for one poll in June 1945 when both Labour and the Conservatives tied on 45%.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The opening ceremony of the 2012 Summer Olympics took place on the evening of Friday 27 July 2012 in the Olympic Stadium, London, during which the Games were formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As mandated by the Olympic Charter, the proceedings combined the ceremonial opening of this international sporting event (including welcoming speeches, hoisting of the flags and the parade of athletes) with an artistic spectacle to showcase the host nation's culture.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The spectacle was entitled ***Isles of Wonder*** and directed by the Academy Award-winning British film director Danny Boyle, with Paulette Randall as associate director.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Prior to London 2012, there had been considerable apprehension about Britain's ability to stage an opening ceremony that could reach the standard set at the Beijing Summer Games of 2008.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 2008 ceremony had been noted for its scale, extravagance and expense, hailed as the "greatest ever", and had cost £65m.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In contrast, London spent an estimated £27m (out of £80m budgeted for its four ceremonies), which was nevertheless about twice the original budget.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Nonetheless, the London opening ceremony was immediately seen as a tremendous success, widely praised as a "masterpiece" and "a love letter to Britain".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony began at 21:00 BST and lasted almost four hours.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was watched by an estimated worldwide television audience of 900 million, falling short of the IOC's 1.5 billion viewership estimate for the 2008 ceremony, but becoming the most viewed in the UK and US.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The content had largely been kept secret before the performance, despite involving thousands of volunteers and two public rehearsals.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The principal sections of the artistic display represented Britain's Industrial Revolution, National Health Service, literary heritage, popular music and culture, and were noted for their vibrant storytelling and use of music.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Two shorter sections drew particular comment, involving a filmed cameo appearance of the Queen with James Bond as her escort, and a live performance by the London Symphony Orchestra joined by comedian Rowan Atkinson.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] These were widely ascribed to Britain's sense of humour.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony featured children and young people in most of its segments, reflecting the "inspire a generation" aspiration of London's original bid for the Games.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The BBC released footage of the entire opening ceremony on 29 October 2012, edited by Danny Boyle and with background extras, along with more than seven hours of sporting highlights and the complete closing ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) approached Danny Boyle to be the director of the ceremony in June 2010, and he immediately accepted.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He said it "felt weirdly more like a ... civic or national responsibility" to take the job.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle acknowledged that the extravagance of the 2008 opening ceremony was an impossible act to follow — "you can't get bigger than Beijing" — and that this realisation had in fact liberated his team creatively.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He said "..obviously I'm not going to try and build on Beijing, because how could you?
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] We can't, and you wouldn't want to, so we're going back to the beginning.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] We're going to try and give the impression that we're rethinking and restarting, because they've (*opening ceremonies*) escalated since Los Angeles in 1984.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They've tried to top themselves each time and you can't do that after Beijing." Beijing's budget had been £65m, whereas London's final budget was £27m, which was twice the original provision.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The London stadium had the same number of seats as Beijing's, but was half the size; this intimacy of scale meant that Boyle felt he could achieve something personal and connecting.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The different sections of the ceremony were designed to reflect aspects of British history and culture, with the title *Isles of Wonder* partly inspired by Shakespeare's play *The Tempest* (particularly Caliban's 'Be not afeard' speech), and partly by the G.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In July 2010, Boyle started brainstorming ideas with designer Mark Tildesley, writer Frank Cottrell-Boyce and costume designer Suttirat Anne Larlarb.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They considered "what was essentially British", with the non-British Larlarb able to offer a view of what the world thought Britain meant.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Cottrell-Boyce had given Boyle a copy of *Pandaemonium*, (named after the capital of Hell in *Paradise Lost*) by Humphrey Jennings, which collated contemporary reports from the Industrial Revolution.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It had become traditional during the opening ceremony to "produce" the Olympic rings in a spectacular manner.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] When Boyle returned to work on the ceremony in the spring of 2011 he asked Rick Smith of Underworld, with whom he had worked on several film projects as well as his theatrical production of Mary Shelley's *Frankenstein*, to be the musical director.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the same time the team moved to the Three Mills studio complex in east London, where a 4x4 metre scale model of the stadium was built.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] For security reasons, a single CGI-assisted version of the ceremony was kept on editor Sascha Dhillon's laptop; anyone needing it had to come to the studio.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The cast included professional performers and 7,500 volunteers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle considered the volunteers to be "the most valuable commodity of all".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In November 2011 they auditioned at Three Mills, and rehearsals began in earnest in spring 2012 at an open-air site at Dagenham (the abandoned Ford plant), often in foul weather.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Although key contributors had to sign non-disclosure agreements and some elements were codenamed, Boyle placed immense trust in the volunteers by asking them simply to "save the surprise" and not leak any information.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Further volunteers were recruited to help with security and marshalling, and to support the technical crew.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Three weeks before the ceremony, Mark Rylance, who was to have taken a leading part, pulled out after a family bereavement and was replaced by Kenneth Branagh.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Olympic Bell, the largest harmonically tuned bell in the world, weighing 23 tonnes, had been cast in brass under the direction of the Whitechapel Bell Foundry by Royal Eijsbouts of the Netherlands, and hung in the Stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was inscribed with a line from Caliban's speech in *The Tempest*: "Be not afeard, the isle is full of noises".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle gave significant emphasis to the London 2012 theme "inspire a generation" and devised a programme relying heavily on children and young people, and built around themes that would relate to the young.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Twenty-five schools in the six original East London host boroughs were used to recruit child volunteers for the performance, and 170 sixth formers (16–18-year-olds), between them speaking more than 50 languages, were recruited from their colleges.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] On 12 June 2012, at a press conference, Boyle had promised a huge set of rural Britain, which was to include a village cricket team, farm animals, a model of Glastonbury Tor, as well as a maypole and a rain-producing cloud.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] His intention was to represent the rural and urban landscape of Britain.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The design was to include a mosh pit at each end of the set, one with people celebrating a rock festival and the other the Last Night of the Proms.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle promised a ceremony with which everyone would feel involved; he said, "I hope it will reveal how peculiar and contrary we are – and how there's also, I hope, a warmth about us." Some of the set was designed with real grass turf and soil.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The use of animals (40 sheep, 12 horses, 3 cows, 2 goats, 10 chickens, 10 ducks, 9 geese and 3 sheep dogs, looked after by 34 animal handlers) drew some criticism from People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle, who was being advised by the RSPCA, assured PETA that the animals would be well cared for.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The overwhelming majority of the music used was British.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The team worked next door to the office of the musical director for the closing ceremony, David Arnold, and so hearing each other's music there was a scramble to claim a particular song first.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rahman, who worked with Boyle on *Slumdog Millionaire* and *127 Hours*, composed a Punjabi song "Nimma Nimma" to showcase Indian influence in the UK, according to Boyle's wishes.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] More Indian music was also scheduled for inclusion in the medley including a Tamil song from the 1989 Bollywood film Ram Lakhan titled "Naanthaan Ungappanda".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Paul McCartney was to be the ceremony's closing act.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Sebastian Coe was instrumental in asking the Queen to take part, responding positively when Boyle first pitched the *Happy and Glorious* film sequence featuring the Queen.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle suggested that the Queen be played either by a lookalike, or by a world-class actress such as Helen Mirren, in a location to double as Buckingham Palace.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Coe asked Princess Anne, a British member of the IOC and LOCOG, what she thought, and she told him to ask the Queen.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Coe presented the idea to the Queen's Deputy Private Secretary.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle was surprised to hear that the Queen would be happy to play herself, and wanted a speaking part.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Filming took place in late March 2012, and *Happy and Glorious* was produced by the BBC, as was the opening film sequence *Journey along the Thames*.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Changes were still being made to the programme in the final days before the ceremony: a BMX bike section was dropped due to time constraints, and the "Pandemonium" and "Thanks..Tim" sections were edited down.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] In 2016 Boyle recounted how he had come under pressure from Jeremy Hunt, then the Olympics and Culture Secretary, to cut back the NHS section, which he had saved only by threatening to resign and take the volunteers with him.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Two full dress and technical rehearsals took place in the Olympic stadium, on 23 and 25 July, in front of an audience of 60,000 comprising volunteers, cast members' families, competition winners, and others connected to the Games.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle asked them not to "spoil the surprise" by using the hashtag #savethesurprise on social media, keeping the performance a secret for the hundreds of millions who would watch on the Friday night.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Seated in the Royal Box were the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, the Prince of Wales, and other members of the British royal family.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] They were accompanied by Archbishop of Canterbury Rowan Williams, Prime Minister David Cameron, Spouse of the Prime Minister Samantha Cameron, former Prime Ministers John Major, Tony Blair and Gordon Brown and Mayor of London Boris Johnson.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Officials of the Olympic movement included President of the IOC Jacques Rogge, LOCOG Chairman Sebastian Coe and members of the IOC.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony was the largest gathering of world leaders for an Olympic and sporting event in history, surpassing that of 2008.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Three multilateral leaders, more than ninety-five heads of state and government and representatives from five organisations and one hundred and twenty countries attended.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At exactly 20:12 BST, the Red Arrows performed a flypast over the Olympic Stadium and then over the concert in Hyde Park.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This concert featured artists selected to represent the four nations of the United Kingdom: Duran Duran, Stereophonics, Snow Patrol and Paolo Nutini.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the beginning the stadium contained a rural scene including the model of Glastonbury Tor, a model village and a water wheel, replete with live animals (removed shortly before the ceremony began), and actors portraying working villagers, football and cricket players.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Frank Turner performed three songs ("Sailor's Boots", "Wessex Boy" and "I Still Believe") on the model of Glastonbury Tor, joined by Emily Barker, Ben Marwood and Jim Lockey, as well as his regular backing band the Sleeping Souls.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This performance celebrated Britain's maritime heritage and geographical insularity.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The ceremony began at 21:00 after a one-minute "60 to 1" countdown film made up of shots of numbers, such as those on house doors, street nameplates, London buses, station platforms and market labels.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The number 39 is seen at the foot of a flight of steps, a reference to John Buchan's novel *The Thirty-Nine Steps*, while the 10 is the door number from 10 Downing Street.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A two-minute film, *Journey along the Thames*, directed by Boyle and produced by the BBC, opened the ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] To the sound of "Surf Solar" by Fuck Buttons, it followed the River Thames from its source to the heart of London, juxtaposing images of contemporary British life with pastoral shots and flashes of scenes from the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The characters Ratty, Mole and Toad from *The Wind in the Willows* were briefly seen, as was a "Monty Python hand" pointing towards London on umbrellas, an InterCity 125 train passing the Olympic rings as crop circles in a field, and a rowing race (to the tune of the "Eton Boating Song").
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At Battersea Power Station a Pink Floyd pig was flying between the towers; the clock sound from another Pink Floyd song "Time" was heard passing Big Ben.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The soundtrack included clips from the theme tune of *The South Bank Show*, "Caprice No.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] 24" (as composed by Andrew Lloyd Webber in his *Variations* fusion album), and the Sex Pistols' "God Save the Queen" as the film followed the route of the band's cruise down the River Thames during the Silver Jubilee.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After lifting to an aerial view of East London mirroring the title sequence of the BBC soap opera *EastEnders*, to the sound of the drum beats from the closing theme, the film flashed down through the Thames Barrier.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It then switched to a sequence filmed outside the stadium shortly before the ceremony, superimposed with posters from previous Summer Olympics (all of them except 1900 Paris, 1936 Berlin, 1984 Los Angeles, and 1996 Atlanta), to a recording of "Map of the Problematique" by Muse.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This ended with a live shot of three cast members holding the posters for the 2012 competition.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] There was then a ten-second countdown in the stadium, with children holding clusters of balloons that burst simultaneously, with the audience shouting out the numbers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bradley Wiggins, who had won the Tour de France five days earlier, opened the ceremony by ringing the Olympic Bell that hung at one end of the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Four upper-atmosphere balloons were released, each expected to carry a set of Olympic rings and a camera up to the mid-stratosphere.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The depiction of rural life already in the arena was billed as "a reminder and a promise of a once and future better life".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] These were inter-cut with footage of notable Rugby Union Home Nations' tries, England's winning drop goal from the 2003 Rugby World Cup Final, and live shots from the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As the last choir performance concluded, vintage London General Omnibus Company stagecoaches entered, carrying businessmen and early industrialists in Victorian dress and top hats, led by Kenneth Branagh as Isambard Kingdom Brunel.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 50 men stepped down from the carriages and surveyed the land approvingly.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After walking onto the Glastonbury Tor, Brunel delivered Caliban's "Be not afeard" speech, reflecting Boyle's introduction to the ceremony in the programme and signifying an aspiration of new industry or a new era in Britain.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This anticipated the next section of the ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section encapsulated British economic and social development from rural economy through the Industrial Revolution to the 1960s.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Proceedings were suddenly interrupted by a loud shout, recorded by volunteers during the rehearsals, followed by drumming (the pre-recorded drumming amplified by 965 cast members drumming on inverted household buckets and bins), led by Evelyn Glennie.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The three-tonne oak tree on top of the Glastonbury Tor lifted, and industrial workers emerged from both the Tor's brightly lit interior and the entrances to the stadium, to swell the cast to a total of 2,500 volunteers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] So began what Boyle had called the "biggest scene change in theatre history" and something he had been advised against attempting.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Underworld's "And I Will Kiss" began to play, as the cast rolled away the grass and other rural props.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Seven smoking chimney stacks with accompanying steeplejacks rose from the ground, along with other industrial machinery: five beam engines, six looms, a crucible and a water wheel (one of the few items left from the rural scene).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle said that this section celebrated the "tremendous potential" afforded by the advancements of the Victorian era.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It also included a minute's silence in remembrance of the loss of life of both world wars, featuring British "Tommies" and shots of poppies, during which the names of the Accrington Pals were shown on the stadium screens.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Unprompted, members of the audience stood in respect during this segment.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Also included were real-life Chelsea Pensioners, the Grimethorpe Colliery Band, and a group of Pearly Kings and Queens.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] As the noise level and tension built, driven by the relentless rhythm of the music and the drumming, participants mimed repetitive mechanical movements associated with industrial processes such as weaving.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Four glowing orange rings gradually began to be carried high above the stadium toward its centre on overhead wires, and then the ring seemingly being cast and forged in the arena began to rise.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The five rings converged, still glowing and accompanied by steam and firework effects to give the impression that they were of hot metal.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] When the five rings formed the Olympic symbol above the stadium, they ignited and rained fire in silver and gold.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The image of the Olympic rings in flame became the iconic image of the ceremony, reproduced in newspapers and web stories around the world.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A short film directed by Boyle and produced by the BBC, called *Happy and Glorious* (after a line in the national anthem), featured the character James Bond, played by then-Bond actor Daniel Craig, entering the front gate of Buckingham Palace in a London black cab.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] His entrance (accompanied by an arrangement of Handel's "Arrival of the Queen of Sheba") is noticed by Brazilian children (a nod to Rio de Janeiro, which was to be the next summer Games host city) in the throne room.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bond meets Elizabeth II (who played herself, acknowledging Bond with the words, "Good evening, Mr Bond") in her audience room at the palace, walks with her out of the building and into a waiting AgustaWestland AW139 helicopter.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The film followed the helicopter across London, with shots of a cheering crowd on The Mall, Nelson's Column, the Palace of Westminster with an animated Winston Churchill statue in Parliament Square, and of the Thames past the London Eye, St Paul's Cathedral, the financial district City of London.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The helicopter then passed through Tower Bridge, accompanied by the Dambusters March.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The film finished with Bond and the Queen apparently jumping from a real helicopter live above the stadium, accompanied by the "James Bond Theme".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, along with Rogge, were then introduced to the audience.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen was wearing the same dress as in the film, as if she had just arrived with Bond.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The idea of the royal helicopter jump was first pitched by director Danny Boyle to Sebastian Coe, who loved it so much he took it to Edward Young, Private Secretary to the Queen, at Buckingham Palace in the summer of 2011.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Young "listened sagely, laughed, and promised to ask the boss".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Word came back to Coe that the Queen would love to take part.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Young, Boyle and Coe agreed to keep the plan secret so as not to spoil the surprise.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] For the scenes with the helicopter, the Queen was doubled by actress Julia McKenzie, and for the parachute jump by BASE jumper and stuntman Gary Connery wearing a dress, hat, jewellery and with a handbag.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The helicopter had flown to the stadium from Stapleford Aerodrome in Essex, piloted by Marc Wolff.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Union Flag was then raised by members of the British Armed Forces, while the first and third verses of the national anthem were performed *a cappella* by the Kaos Signing Choir for Deaf and Hearing Children.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The first part of this sequence celebrated the National Health Service ("the institution which more than any other unites our nation", according to the programme), which had been founded in the year of the previous London Games in 1948.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Six hundred dancers, some of whom were NHS staff, along with 1,200 volunteers, some recruited from British hospitals, entered along with children on 320 hospital beds, some of which functioned as trampolines.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Watching from the tor were specially invited hospital staff and nine child patients from Great Ormond Street Hospital.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The blankets on the beds illuminated and the beds were arranged to depict a child's face with a smile and a tear (the Hospital Children's Charity's logo).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The acronym "GOSH" then changed into the initials "NHS", turning into the shape of a crescent moon as the children were hushed to sleep and read books by the nurses.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sequence then moved on to celebrate British children's literature.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Barrie's *Peter Pan* (whose copyright was given to Great Ormond Street Hospital).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Child Catcher appeared amongst the children, followed by giant puppet representations of villains from British children's literature: the Queen of Hearts, Captain Hook, Cruella de Vil, and Lord Voldemort.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Minutes later, 32 women playing Mary Poppins descended with their umbrellas, as the villains deflated and the actors resumed dancing.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The music for this sequence included partially rearranged sections from *Tubular Bells* (with a giant set of tubular bells at the rear of the stage), *Tubular Bells III* and, after the villains had been driven away by the Mary Poppins characters, *In Dulci Jubilo*.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] During this performance the children in pyjamas jumped up and down on their brightly lit beds, creating a memorable image amid the darkness of the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sequence concluded with a pale, gigantic baby's head, with a rippling sheet for its body, in the centre of the arena.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This celebrated the Scottish pioneers of obstetric ultrasound imaging.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Simon Rattle was then introduced to conduct the London Symphony Orchestra in a performance of Vangelis's "Chariots of Fire", as a tribute to the British film industry with Rowan Atkinson reprising his role as Mr.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Bean, comically playing a repeated note on a synthesiser.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He then lapsed into a filmed dream sequence in which he joined the runners from the film *Chariots of Fire*, beating them in their iconic run along West Sands at St Andrews by riding in a car, rejoining the race and tripping the front runner.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Danny Boyle later said: "It wasn't actually Mr.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Strictly speaking, the name of his character was Derek." In 2021's *Happy Birthday Mr Bean* documentary, Atkinson also stated that the performance was not actually intended to be the character Mr.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This sequence celebrated British popular music and culture, paying homage to each decade since the 1960s.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] To the accompaniment of the BBC newsreel theme "Girls in Grey" and the theme tune from *The Archers*, a young mother and son arrive in a Mini Cooper at a full-size replica of a modern British house.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 1987 "don't worry about a hurricane" weather forecast by Michael Fish was shown on the big screens as rain suddenly poured on the house, followed by "Push the Button", by Sugababes.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] During this track images of the Underground were projected onto the house and former London Mayor Ken Livingstone was briefly seen driving the train.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Throughout the sequence cast members were texting each other or placing social networking status updates on the Internet.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Frankie and June first notice each other as a snippet from "Wonderful Tonight" by Eric Clapton plays, but when Frankie saw that June had dropped her phone on the Tube, he set off to return it (communicating using last number redial to her sister's phone).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] At the close, while "Heaven" by Emeli Sandé was played, the larger house was raised to reveal Tim Berners-Lee working at a NeXT Computer, like the one on which he invented the World Wide Web.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He tweeted "This is for everyone", instantly spelt out in LED lights around the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The programme explained "Music connects us with each other and with the most important moments in our lives.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] One of the things that makes those connections possible is the World Wide Web".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Boyle wanted to honour Berners-Lee for having made the World Wide Web free and available to everyone (hence the tweet), rather than seeking a commercial profit from it.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A filmed sequence showed extracts from the torch relay around the UK, to the music "I Heard Wonders" by David Holmes.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This then cut live to show David Beckham driving a dramatically illuminated motor boat down the River Thames and under Tower Bridge, to fireworks, while footballer Jade Bailey held on to the torch in the boat.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section had been rehearsed on 24 July 2012 when the close-up shots were pre-recorded, and was directed by Stephen Daldry.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] There was then a tribute to "..friends and family of those in the stadium who cannot be here tonight", including the victims of the "7/7" 2005 London bombings (on the day after London had been awarded the Games).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Photos of people who had died were displayed on screens as a memorial, accompanied by an excerpt from Brian Eno's ambient work "An Ending (Ascent)".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The hymn "Abide with Me" was then sung by Emeli Sandé while a group of dancers choreographed by and including Akram Khan performed a contemporary dance on the theme of mortality.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Parade of Nations of athletes (drawn from the 10,490 competing) and officials from 204 nations (and also the "Independent Olympic Athletes") was led, according to custom, by the Greek team, followed by other competing countries in alphabetical order, and finally the host nation Great Britain.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Welsh drum and bass DJ High Contrast mixed and sequenced the music for the athletes' parade.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Once all of the athletes were inside the stadium, seven billion small pieces of paper were dropped from a Westland helicopter, each piece representing one person on Earth.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Each nation's flag was planted on the Glastonbury Tor.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Once the athletes had gathered in the centre of the stadium, Arctic Monkeys performed "I Bet You Look Good on the Dancefloor" and The Beatles' "Come Together", the latter while 75 cyclists circled the stadium with wings lit by LEDs representing Doves of Peace.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Doves were traditionally released at Olympic opening ceremonies, although real birds have not been used since 1992.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A single dove cyclist, his beak painted yellow in honour of Bradley Wiggins, appeared to fly out of the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The formal part of the ceremony was introduced by Sebastian Coe, speaking from the Tor and surrounded by flags of the participating nations.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He welcomed the watching world to London.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He expressed pride in being British and part of the Olympic movement, and said that the Olympics "brings together the people of the world...to celebrate what is best about mankind".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He continued to speak of the "truth and drama" of sport, and then thanked Britain for "making all this possible".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge responded by thanking London, stating that it was the third time that London had held the Games, following 1908, held at short notice when Rome was unable to do so (after a volcanic eruption), and 1948 three years after the end of World War II.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge thanked the thousands of volunteers, to huge cheers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He announced that for the first time in Olympic history, every team had female participants.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Rogge acknowledged the important role the UK had played as "the birthplace of modern sport", codifying its "fair play" ethos and building sport into the school curriculum.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He appealed to athletes to play fairly and be drug-free, according to the values of Baron de Coubertin, reminding them that they were role models who would "inspire a generation".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] After expressing these sentiments again briefly in French, he invited the Queen to open the Games.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The Queen declared the competition officially open, immediately followed by a trumpet fanfare based on a theme from *Tubular Bells* by Mike Oldfield and then a fireworks display.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The 2012 ceremony was the second time the Queen had opened an Olympic Games, the first being the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal in her capacity as Queen of Canada.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] It was also the first time any individual had opened a Summer Olympics twice (two more Olympiads had been opened on her behalf, with a further two Winter Games opened on her behalf).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The flag paused in front of Muhammad Ali (invited to represent "respect, confidence, conviction, dedication, generosity and spiritual strength"), who held it for a few moments.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The flag was received by a colour guard of Her Majesty's Armed Forces and hoisted to the Olympic Anthem, performed by the LSO and the Grimethorpe Colliery Band.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A brief reprise of "And I will Kiss" commenced the Olympic Oaths, taken by taekwondo athlete Sarah Stevenson on behalf of the athletes, by British AIBA Referee Mik Basi on behalf of the officials, and by Eric Farrell on behalf of the coaches.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This section was named after the song of the same name by The Smiths.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The motorboat driven by David Beckham arrived with the Olympic Flame via the Limehouse Cut and the Lee Navigation.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Steve Redgrave lit his torch from that on the boat, and carried it into the stadium through an honour guard of 500 of the construction workers who had built the Olympic Park.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] He passed the flame on to a team of seven young people, each nominated by a famous British Olympian to convey the Games' aim to "inspire a generation".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Six of the team were athletes, and the seventh was a volunteer young ambassador.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The teenagers made a lap of the stadium, each carrying the torch in turn, while Alex Trimble, lead singer of Two Door Cinema Club, performed "Caliban's Dream" with the Dockhead Choir, Only Men Aloud, Elizabeth Roberts, and Esme Smith.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] This had been written especially for the ceremony by Rick Smith of Underworld.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Each young athlete was greeted by their nominating Olympian (watched by 260 British medallists from previous summer and winter Games since London 1948) and presented with their own torch, which was then lit from the flame.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The young athletes lit some of the petals, and when the flame had spread to all of them, the pipes rose slowly from the floor of the stadium and converged to form the cauldron.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The cauldron designed by Thomas Heatherwick was described as "one of the best-kept secrets of the opening ceremony": until this point, its design, location, and who would light it had not been revealed.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] A flurry of spectacular fireworks accompanied by Pink Floyd's song "Eclipse" was supported by images of memorable Olympic victories shown on the big screens, with the stadium pixels showing Jesse Owens running.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The climax of this section was a live view of the Olympic rings 34 kilometres (21 miles) above the Earth, transmitted from one of the balloons launched three and a half hours earlier.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] The sky was then lit by searchlights piercing the smoke (another iconic London image) from the fireworks, the Orbit tower was illuminated.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p01] Paul McCartney and his band performed the closing section of "The End", and then "Hey Jude", with its chorus sung by the audience to close the ceremony at 00:46 BST.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The eclectic programme of music was chosen to showcase almost exclusively British music with pieces representing the UK's four nations.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It included classical works by British composers such as Hubert Parry, and performances by UK choirs and orchestras.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The focus was mainly on music of the 1960s onwards, causing one Chinese journalist to ask: "Will this be the most rock and roll opening ceremony ever?".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Rick Smith and Underworld composed pieces for the ceremony, including "And I Will Kiss" used during the "Pandemonium" section, and "Caliban's Dream" heard during the lighting of the cauldron.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These were favourably reviewed; in *The Guardian*, Michael Hann wrote "Underworld ... had a bit of a triumph: the builds and fades they learned in the world of dance music lent the sometimes overwhelming visual spectacle a sense of structure".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Bells were a theme of the opening day of the Olympics, starting at 8:12 am with artist Martin Creed's *Work No.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 1197: All the Bells*, when bells were rung across the UK including forty strikes of Big Ben.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] "The sound of bells is the sound of England", Boyle had told volunteers during rehearsal.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Much of the music for the ceremony contained "bell" references, linking to the large bell forged for the ceremony and evoking bells as "the sound of freedom and peace".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Modified sequences based on the traditional British eight-bell peal underlaid "And I Will Kiss" and carried through into the "Tubular Bells"/NHS section, with handbells and a tolling large bell featured on "Caliban's Dream" and at key points in the ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A handbell chime also played after the close, as the stadium emptied.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle approached many of the artists personally, to see if they would be interested in performing, and he also flew to Barbados for an hour-long meeting with Mike Oldfield.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A few turned him down, including Elvis Costello and David Bowie.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The performing artists were paid a nominal £1 fee to make their contracts legally binding.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The pre-recorded soundtrack *Isles of Wonder* was released on iTunes at midnight of 28 July 2012, with a two-disc CD set released on 2 August.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Within two days, the download album had topped the iTunes album charts in Britain, France, Belgium and Spain, and reached No.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 5 in the United States, as well as being No.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Rick Smith's concluding comment in the CD cover notes was: "The isle is full of noises.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The main loading of the stadium started on 10 May and took ten weeks of what was the wettest summer for a hundred years, posing considerable challenges.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Dismantling the staging took just sixty hours.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The infield staging area was 2.5 metres high, and had to accommodate the elements revealed during the ceremony, such as the chimneys and beam engines from "Pandemonium", and the cauldron.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] To ensure that it remained secret, the cauldron was code-named "Betty", and installed and tested at night.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The stadium was rigged with a one million watt sound system and more than 500 speakers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Some 15,000 square metres (3.7 acres) of staging and 12,956 props were used, as well as 7,346 square metres (1.815 acres) of turf including crops.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] 70,799 25 centimetre (10 inch) pixel panels were placed around the stadium, including between every seat.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Each panel connected to a central computer and was fitted with nine full-colour LED pixels by Tait Technology.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These enabled images to be broadcast during the performance, such as of a 1960s go-go dancer, a London Underground train, and a representation of the birth of the internet.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The audience was also able to participate by waving the paddles to create a twinkling effect.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These animations were designed by 59 Productions and the video animations were produced by Chinese company Crystal CG.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The 2D to 3D transformation and mapping of video content onto the panels were done by Avolites Media media server consoles.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Technical director Piers Shepperd masterminded the complex change from rural to industrial during "Pandemonium".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The seven inflatable chimneys were made by Airworks, and varied in height (three were 22-metre (72 ft), two were 23-metre (75 ft) and two were 30-metre (98 ft) high).
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] They were made of soft fabric, with an outer layer of printed brick pattern.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Each contained four industrial fans at the base to inflate them, and a smoke machine near the top, and were hoisted into the air from the overhead rigs.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Life-size beam engines were constructed onstage by teams of stage hands and members of the Volunteer Staging Team.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] At the climax of "Pandemonium", in the Olympic ring forging scene, amber lights lit in sequence created the illusion of a 30-metre (98 ft) molten steel river, with pyrotechnic smoke and dry ice as steam.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The original grass floor surface had been removed to reveal a giant stylised map of London.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Working alongside the professional crew were more than 800 volunteers; some were production arts students from British drama schools.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Many had been working on the Olympic and Paralympic ceremonies since early 2012 at the Three Mills Studios and Dagenham rehearsal sites, before moving to the Stadium on 16 June.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The thousands of cast were cued and co-ordinated by directions received through earphones ("in-ear monitors"), and adjustments were made during the performance: for example, during Pandemonium extra volunteers were sent to make sure all the turf was cleared on time.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The earphones also carried a continuous electronic metronomic four-beat to keep everyone walking and moving in time with the music.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In July 2013 it was revealed that on the morning of the ceremony, Britain's surveillance headquarters GCHQ had detected a credible cyber attack threat that could have killed the lighting system in the stadium.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Counter-measures were taken, and in the afternoon contingency plans were discussed with government ministers at a meeting in the Cabinet Office briefing room.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] However, this attack never materialised.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC's coverage started at 19:00 and continued uninterrupted until 00:50.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC audience averaged about 24.46 million viewers and peaked at approximately 26.9 million.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This was the largest average audience for any broadcast since 1996 and one of the top 20 most-watched UK television broadcasts of all time.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] David Stringer of Associated Press described the coverage as "a success...so far, the BBC's ambitious – and technically tricky – Olympic plan has worked almost without a flaw." Euan Ferguson of *The Observer* commented that "Coverage of the Olympics so far ... has been near perfect".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] However, Clive James was critical of the build-up programme, presented by Gary Lineker and Sue Barker.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Commentators for the BBC were Huw Edwards, Hazel Irvine and Trevor Nelson, the latter criticised by Andy Dawson of the *Daily Mirror* as floundering "like a ventriloquist's dummy pumped full of low-grade ketamine".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Private talks were held between Boyle and BBC commentators in the run-up to the ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle was unhappy with a voiceover being imposed on the ceremony, which he wanted viewers to be able to enjoy without commentary.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC offered several options including "no commentary" coverage for both its TV and online transmissions.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Audio description was also provided with commentary by Nick Mullins.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Nearly 41 million US viewers watched NBC's coverage of the event.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Criticism was levelled at its decision to tape-delay this broadcast, and not make a live version available even to cable and web users.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There were frequent interruptions by commercial breaks.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Many US viewers looked for other ways to watch (such as the live BBC feed), despite both NBC and the IOC vowing to crack down on unauthorised streams.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] More significant criticism was levelled at NBC for cutting to a Ryan Seacrest interview with Michael Phelps during the "memorial wall" tribute including commemoration of the victims of the 7/7 London bombings, which was seen as disrespectful and insensitive.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] An NBC spokesman said the network had left out that segment because its programming was "tailored for the US audience".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There was also criticism of commentators Matt Lauer and Meredith Vieira for suggesting that the Queen had actually jumped out of a helicopter.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Vieira and Lauer admitted to not knowing that Tim Berners-Lee was the inventor of the World Wide Web, as she commented "If you haven't heard of him, we haven't either", before Lauer told the audience to Google him.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] These failings were picked up on Twitter during the broadcast with the hashtag #nbcfail.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was recorded by three separate broadcasters: the BBC, the Olympic Broadcasting Services (directed by the Finnish state broadcaster YLE on behalf of the OBS), and by independent production company Done and Dusted, hired by LOCOG and working under Boyle's direction.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This was the first time that an independent production company had been used for an Olympic ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] This situation led to some tension, as Boyle wanted more artistic control and felt he was getting no co-operation from the OBS.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] He criticised the OBS coverage during his commentary for the BBC DVD.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In addition, the BBC filmed some of the pre-recorded parts of the ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The filming was directed for television by Hamish Hamilton, who described it as "easily the most difficult job of my life".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC released footage of the entire ceremony on 29 October 2012, edited by Danny Boyle and with background extras, filling more than one disc of a five DVD or Blu-ray disc set, which also contained more than seven hours of sporting highlights as well as the complete closing ceremony.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A "BBC commentary-free" option for the opening ceremony is available on the DVD, as well as a commentary track by Danny Boyle and Frank Cottrell-Boyce.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Although praise came from across the political spectrum, a few on the British political right were unhappy.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Aidan Burley, a Conservative MP, denounced the ceremony on Twitter as "leftie multicultural crap".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Burley's comments were dismissed by many fellow Conservatives, including David Cameron and Boris Johnson.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Foreign reaction was overwhelmingly positive.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The New York Times* said the ceremony was "hilariously quirky ... a wild jumble of the celebratory and the fanciful; the conventional and the eccentric; and the frankly off-the-wall".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *Forbes* called it Boyle's "love song to Britain", while *Sports Illustrated* noted its political aspects, calling it "a celebration of protest and dissent".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The Sydney Morning Herald* said it was "an unforgettable start ... at once subversive and sublime" and *The Times of India* said that "London presented a vibrant picture of Great Britain's rich heritage and culture".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The Chinese news agency *Xinhua* described the ceremony as "dazzling" and an "eccentric and exuberant celebration of British history, art and culture".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Russian President Putin said the ceremony was "wonderful and unforgettable".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] French sports newspaper *L'Équipe* wrote that the ceremony "took the classic from such events and had fun with them", while *Le Parisien* said it "was magnificent, inventive and offbeat drawing heavily on the roots of British identity".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Germany's *Die Welt* hailed it as "spectacular, glitzy but also provoking and moving".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Chinese news CCTV-4 said the ceremony was a "stunning feast for the eyes".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] South Korea's Yonhap said it was "by turns dramatic, imaginative, humorous and solemn" and "weaved the story of the country's past, present and future".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Singapore's *Straits Times* said it was a "grand show" noteworthy for both "scale" and "authenticity".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] *The Australian* praised a "glorious pandemonium devoted to London's thriving, chaotic energy ... deliberately revelling in the chaos of Britain's free society and popular culture".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] France's *Le Figaro* said the ceremony reflected "the best contributions that Britain has given to the world ... its sense of humour, its music, and of course sport".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation said it was a "rocking, rollicking, sometimes quiet and brooding ceremony".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Qatar's *The Peninsula* said that London did a "spectacular job" making the ceremony a "memorable event".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In an end of the year review, British magazine *Q* said "It could all have been so different.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] As the London 2012 Summer Olympics approached, the tide of scepticism seemed almost irreversible.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] There was the heavy-handed sponsorship, the draconian security, the ticketing problems, the ballooning budget, and the lurking fear that the Opening Ceremony might be, in director Danny Boyle's pungent description, 'shite'.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It took less than four hours on the night of Friday 27 July to turn the whole country around.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The writer of the ceremony, Frank Cottrell-Boyce, said: "People around us thought it might need defending, so I was told to do press the next morning.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] I was completely surprised *[by the positive response]*.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] At no point did he show any feeling that it was going to be anything but amazing.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] In December 2012 the culture critic of *The Guardian* picked the ceremony as "best art event of the year".
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A British public survey by Samsung voted it the second most inspiring television moment of all time, second only to the 1969 Apollo 11 Moon landing.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] A Digital Spy survey of more than 25,000 overwhelmingly voted the ceremony as the entertainment highlight of 2012.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was the second most-mentioned entertainment event on the internet in 2012, with just over six million mentions, coming second to the Grammy Awards.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The BBC reported that it was the most requested item from 2012 on its iPlayer on-demand service, with 3.3 million requests.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] The ceremony was identified by some commentators as precipitating a new mood in the United Kingdom: it "had barely finished before it had become a byword for a new approach, not only to British culture but to Britishness itself.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Politicians would soon be referring to it, using it as shorthand for a new kind of patriotism that does not lament a vanished Britain but loves the country that has changed.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle's ceremony was hailed from (almost) all sides...for providing a nation that had grown used to mocking its myriad flaws with a new, unfamiliarly positive view of itself ...
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] It was, perhaps, this lack of cynicism that people responded to ...
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] So used to British irony and detachment, it felt refreshing to witness an unembarrassed, positive case for this country.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Boyle himself says this was the most important thing he took away from the Olympic experience: "How important it is to believe in something.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Business leaders also took inspiration from the event, admiring its risk-taking and creative freedom, as well as the trust placed in and loyalty inspired from the workers and volunteers.
[src:national-health-service/2012-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony-p02] Reviewing the 2014 Winter Olympics opening ceremony at Sochi, Russia, Owen Gibson of *The Guardian* observed that with his "complex, intimate snapshot of 'who we were, who we are and who we wish to be'", Boyle "rewrote the rule book for opening ceremonies".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] "**A Bridge over You**" is a charity single recorded and released independently by the Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Choir, the choir of the Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust located in south-east London.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It is a mashup of "Bridge over Troubled Water" by Simon & Garfunkel and Coldplay's 2005 single "Fix You", with additional arrangement by the choir's conductor, Peter Mitchell.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It reached number one on the UK Singles Chart at Christmas 2015.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] The Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Choir had previously appeared on the first series of Gareth Malone's BBC Two show *The Choir: Sing While You Work*, a competition between workplace choirs, in 2012.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] "A Bridge over You" was recorded in 2013, following the choir's appearance in the competition.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It was recorded at Angel Recording Studios in Islington, north London, with piano accompaniment by Liam Dunachie, guitars by Ed Cusick, bass by Sam Weston, drums by Christian Rae, and vocal direction by Dan Ludford and Peter Mitchell.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] The single was created and arranged by Adam Morris, with additional arrangements made by Peter Mitchell and Liam Dunachie.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] At the time of recording, the choir's artistic director was Dan Ludford-Thomas, the musical director Peter Mitchell, and the accompanist Liam Dunachie.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] An accompanying video featuring the song over footage of NHS staff working at the Trust was uploaded to YouTube.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] At the time, Secretary of State for Health Jeremy Hunt was debating extending the contracted hours of junior doctors, a move that proved controversial and which prompted the British Medical Association to consider strike action.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Nerva created a Facebook event for the campaign after the video "moved [her] to tears", telling Mirror Online that "getting it to Number One would bring to the public's eye the fantastic service it provides in very challenging times".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Rogerson told *The Guardian* that "it's a challenging time for the NHS and morale is quite low ...
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] On 13 January 2016, the UK Government announced that the value-added tax on sales of the single—16.5p from every 99p sale—would be donated to charity.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] "A Bridge over You" was originally released independently by Blunden on behalf of the NHS Trust through EmuBands on 9 December 2013 in support of various charities including Carers UK, Mind and other smaller healthcare related charities.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] The 2015 campaign's organisers asked supporters not to purchase the song until the week of the Christmas charts so as to focus sales.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] On the week of the Christmas charts, Justin Bieber, whose song "Love Yourself" was the favourite for the accolade, tweeted his support for the choir's song: "For 1 week it's ok not be #1.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Let's do the right thing & help them win.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It's Christmas." Following his tweet, bookmaker Coral suspended betting on the odds of the single reaching number 1.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] On Christmas Eve, itv.com commented that the choir "now look unbeatable".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It reached number one on the UK Singles Chart at Christmas 2015, selling more than 127,000 copies, 88,000 sales fewer than Ben Haenow's 2014 Christmas number one "Something I Need".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It beat off competition from Bieber as well as *The X Factor* winner Louisa Johnson, Adele, and Stormzy.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] It was the closest run-in to the Christmas number one since 2009, when Jon Morter's anti-*X Factor* social media campaign resulted in Rage Against the Machine's 1992 single "Killing in the Name" taking the accolade ahead of the competition's winner Joe McElderry.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Blunden was in regular contact with Morter during the campaign for his previous experience with Christmas chart campaigns.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Blunden, who was manager of the #NHS4XmasNo1 campaign, told *The Telegraph* on Christmas Day that "it's an historic day for the NHS...a day that the country has shown just how much they love their NHS".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Zoe Davies, a medical registrar who sings part of the opening solo, told *The Northern Echo* that "it gives the NHS a morale boost at a time of uncertainty about junior doctors' contracts and nurses' bursaries being taken away".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Chidi Ejimofo, a Consultant in Emergency Medicine who sang the male solo part, told *the South London Press* "...it is about so much more than the front line doctors and nurses.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] This song celebrates the work of all the unsung heroes in the NHS, whose amazing work is often taken for granted.".
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] In its second week on the UK Singles Chart, the song broke the record for the biggest fall for a UK number one single, when it fell to number 29 on 1 January 2016.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Previously, the record had been held by McFly's "Baby's Coming Back/Transylvania", which fell from number 1 to number 20 on 20 May 2007.
[src:national-health-service/a-bridge-over-you] Credits adapted from the website of the Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Choir.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] There is a range of acupuncture technological variants that originated in different philosophies, and techniques vary depending on the country in which it is performed.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is most often used to attempt pain relief, though acupuncturists say that it can also be used for a wide range of other conditions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is typically used in combination with other forms of treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The global acupuncture market was worth US$24.55 billion in 2017.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The market was led by Europe with a 32.7% share, followed by Asia-Pacific with a 29.4% share and the Americas with a 25.3% share.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It was estimated in 2021 that the industry would reach a market size of US$55 billion by 2023.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The conclusions of trials and systematic reviews of acupuncture generally provide no good evidence of benefits, which suggests that it is not an effective method of healthcare.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is generally safe when done by appropriately trained practitioners using clean needle techniques and single-use needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] When properly delivered, it has a low rate of mostly minor adverse effects.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] When accidents and infections do occur, they are associated with neglect on the part of the practitioner, particularly in the application of sterile techniques.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A review conducted in 2013 stated that reports of infection transmission increased significantly in the preceding decade.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The most frequently reported adverse events were pneumothorax and infections.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Since serious adverse events continue to be reported, it is recommended that acupuncturists be trained sufficiently to reduce the risk.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Scientific investigation has not found any histological or physiological evidence for traditional Chinese concepts such as *qi*, meridians, and acupuncture points, and many modern practitioners no longer support the existence of *qi* or meridians, which was a major part of early belief systems.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is believed to have originated around 100 BC in China, around the time *The Inner Classic of Huang Di* (*Huangdi Neijing*) was published, though some experts suggest it could have been practiced earlier.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Over time, conflicting claims and belief systems emerged about the effect of lunar, celestial and earthly cycles, yin and yang energies, and a body's "rhythm" on the effectiveness of treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture fluctuated in popularity in China due to changes in the country's political leadership and the preferential use of rationalism or scientific evidence-based medicine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture spread first to Korea in the 6th century AD, then to Japan through medical missionaries, and then to Europe, beginning with France.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In the 20th century, as it spread to the United States and Western countries, spiritual elements of acupuncture that conflicted with scientific knowledge were sometimes abandoned in favor of simply tapping needles into acupuncture points.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is a form of alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It is used most commonly for pain relief, though it is also used to treat a wide range of conditions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is generally only used in combination with other forms of treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] For example, the American Society of Anesthesiologists states it may be considered in the treatment of nonspecific, noninflammatory low back pain only in conjunction with conventional therapy.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is the insertion of thin needles into the skin.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] According to the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research (Mayo Clinic), a typical session entails lying still while approximately five to twenty needles are inserted; for the majority of cases, the needles will be left in place for ten to twenty minutes.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It can be associated with the application of heat, pressure, or laser light.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Classically, acupuncture is individualized and based on philosophy and intuition, and not on scientific research.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] There is also a non-invasive therapy developed in early 20th-century Japan using an elaborate set of instruments other than needles for the treatment of children (*shōnishin* or *shōnihari*).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Clinical practice varies depending on the country.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A comparison of the average number of patients treated per hour found significant differences between China (10) and the United States (1.2).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] There is a diverse range of acupuncture approaches, involving different philosophies.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although various different techniques of acupuncture practice have emerged, the method used in traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) seems to be the most widely adopted in the US.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Traditional acupuncture involves needle insertion, moxibustion, and cupping therapy, and may be accompanied by other procedures such as feeling the pulse and other parts of the body and examining the tongue.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Traditional acupuncture involves the belief that a "life force" (*qi*) circulates within the body in lines called meridians.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The main methods practiced in the UK are TCM and Western medical acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The term Western medical acupuncture is used to indicate an adaptation of TCM-based acupuncture which focuses less on TCM.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The Western medical acupuncture approach involves using acupuncture after a medical diagnosis.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Limited research has compared the contrasting acupuncture systems used in various countries for determining different acupuncture points, and thus there is no defined standard for acupuncture points.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In traditional acupuncture, the acupuncturist decides which points to treat by observing and questioning the patient to make a diagnosis according to the tradition used.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In TCM, the four diagnostic methods are: inspection, auscultation and olfaction, inquiring, and palpation.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Inspection focuses on the face and particularly on the tongue, including analysis of the tongue placement, size, shape, tension, color and coating, and the absence or presence of teeth marks around the edge.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Auscultation and olfaction involve listening for particular sounds, such as wheezing, and observing body odor.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Inquiring involves focusing on the "seven inquiries": chills and fever; perspiration; appetite, thirst and taste; defecation and urination; pain; sleep; and menses and leukorrhea.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Palpation is focusing on feeling the body for tender *A-shi* points and feeling the pulse.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The most common mechanism of stimulation of acupuncture points employs penetration of the skin by thin metal needles, which are manipulated manually or the needle may be further stimulated by electrical stimulation (electroacupuncture).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture needles are typically made of stainless steel, making them flexible and preventing them from rusting or breaking.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Needles are usually disposed of after each use to prevent contamination.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Reusable needles when used should be sterilized between applications.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In many areas, only sterile, single-use acupuncture needles are allowed, including the State of California.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Needles vary in length between 13 and 130 millimetres (0.51 and 5.12 in), with shorter needles used near the face and eyes, and longer needles in areas with thicker tissues; needle diameters vary from 0.16 mm (0.006 in) to 0.46 mm (0.018 in), with thicker needles used on more robust patients.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Thinner needles may be flexible and require tubes for insertion.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The tip of the needle should not be made too sharp to prevent breakage, although blunt needles cause more pain.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Apart from the usual filiform needle, other needle types include three-edged needles and the Nine Ancient Needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Japanese acupuncturists use extremely thin needles that are used superficially, sometimes without penetrating the skin, and surrounded by a guide tube (a 17th-century invention adopted in China and the West).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Korean acupuncture uses copper needles and has a greater focus on the hand.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The skin is sterilized and needles are inserted, frequently with a plastic guide tube.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Needles may be manipulated in various ways, including spinning, flicking, or moving up and down relative to the skin.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Since most pain is felt in the superficial layers of the skin, a quick insertion of the needle is recommended.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Often the needles are stimulated by hand in order to cause a dull, localized, aching sensation that is called *de qi*, as well as "needle grasp," a tugging feeling felt by the acupuncturist and generated by a mechanical interaction between the needle and skin.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The acupuncturist's skill level may influence the painfulness of the needle insertion; a sufficiently skilled practitioner may be able to insert the needles without causing any pain.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Once **de-qi** is observed, techniques might be used which attempt to "influence" the **de-qi**; for example, by certain manipulation the **de-qi** can allegedly be conducted from the needling site towards more distant sites of the body.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Other techniques aim at "tonifying" (Chinese: 补; pinyin: *bǔ*) or "sedating" (Chinese: 泄; pinyin: *xiè*) *qi*.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The former techniques are used in deficiency patterns, the latter in excess patterns.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] *De qi* is more important in Chinese acupuncture, while Western and Japanese patients may not consider it a necessary part of the treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] As of 2021, many thousands of papers had been published on the efficacy of acupuncture for the treatment of various adult health conditions, but there was no robust evidence it was beneficial for anything, except shoulder pain and fibromyalgia.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The evidence for its efficacy in shoulder pain is low quality and includes only two studies.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Its efficacy for fibromyalgia does not appear to be clinically significant.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Harriet Hall noticed that according to Edzard Ernst in 2011, systematic reviews agreed that acupuncture works for neck pain, but not for every other pain—and that makes its whole enterprise suspicious.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2024 review concluded that it is no more effective than sham acupuncture for neck pain reduction.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It is difficult but not impossible to design rigorous research trials for acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Due to acupuncture's invasive nature, one of the major challenges in efficacy research is in the design of an appropriate placebo control group.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] For efficacy studies to determine whether acupuncture has specific effects, "sham" forms of acupuncture where the patient, practitioner, and analyst are blinded seem the most acceptable approach.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Sham acupuncture uses non-penetrating needles or needling at non-acupuncture points, e.g. inserting needles on meridians not related to the specific condition being studied, or in places not associated with meridians.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The under-performance of acupuncture in such trials may indicate that therapeutic effects are due entirely to non-specific effects, or that the sham treatments are not inert, or that systematic protocols yield less than optimal treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The same analysis also suggested that the number of needles and sessions is important, as greater numbers improved the outcomes of acupuncture compared to non-acupuncture controls.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] There has been little systematic investigation of which components of an acupuncture session may be important for any therapeutic effect, including needle placement and depth, type and intensity of stimulation, and number of needles used.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The research seems to suggest that needles do not need to stimulate the traditionally specified acupuncture points or penetrate the skin to attain an anticipated effect (e.g. psychosocial factors).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A response to "sham" acupuncture in osteoarthritis may be used in the elderly, but placebos have usually been regarded as deception and thus unethical.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] However, some physicians and ethicists have suggested circumstances for applicable uses for placebos such as it might present a theoretical advantage of an inexpensive treatment without adverse reactions or interactions with drugs or other medications.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] As the evidence for most types of alternative medicine such as acupuncture is far from strong, the use of alternative medicine in regular healthcare can present an ethical question.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Using the principles of evidence-based medicine to research acupuncture is controversial, and has produced different results.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Some research suggests acupuncture can alleviate pain but the majority of research suggests that acupuncture's effects are mainly due to placebo.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Evidence suggests that any benefits of acupuncture are short-lasting.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] There is insufficient evidence to support use of acupuncture compared to mainstream medical treatments.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is not better than mainstream treatment in the long term.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The use of acupuncture has been criticized owing to there being little scientific evidence for explicit effects, or the mechanisms for its supposed effectiveness, for any condition that is discernible from placebo.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture has been called "theatrical placebo", and David Gorski argues that when acupuncture proponents advocate "harnessing of placebo effects" or work on developing "meaningful placebos", they essentially concede it is little more than that.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Medical doctors practicing acupuncture cannot agree upon the positions of acupuncture points, to the extent it has become meaningless to call them "points".
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Publication bias is cited as a concern in the reviews of randomized controlled trials of acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 1998 review of studies on acupuncture found that trials originating in China, Japan, Hong Kong, and Taiwan were uniformly favourable to acupuncture, as were ten out of eleven studies conducted in Russia.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The study also found that trials published in non-Chinese journals tended to be of higher quality.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Chinese authors use more Chinese studies, which have been demonstrated to be uniformly positive.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2012 review of 88 systematic reviews of acupuncture published in Chinese journals found that less than half of these reviews reported testing for publication bias, and that the majority of these reviews were published in journals with impact factors of zero.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2015 study comparing pre-registered records of acupuncture trials with their published results found that it was uncommon for such trials to be registered before the trial began.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] This study also found that selective reporting of results and changing outcome measures to obtain statistically significant results was common in this literature.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Scientist Steven Salzberg identifies acupuncture and Chinese medicine generally as a focus for "fake medical journals" such as the *Journal of Acupuncture and Meridian Studies* and *Acupuncture in Medicine*.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] As Singh and Ernst pointed out, Chinese publication bias for acupuncture is real, without being fraud.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is generally safe when administered by an experienced, appropriately trained practitioner using clean-needle technique and sterile single-use needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] When improperly delivered it can cause adverse effects.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Accidents and infections are associated with infractions of sterile technique or neglect on the part of the practitioner.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] To reduce the risk of serious adverse events after acupuncture, acupuncturists should be trained sufficiently.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2009 overview of Cochrane reviews found acupuncture is not effective for a wide range of conditions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] People with serious spinal disease, such as cancer or infection, are not good candidates for acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Contraindications to acupuncture (conditions that should not be treated with acupuncture) include coagulopathy disorders (e.g. hemophilia and advanced liver disease), warfarin use, severe psychiatric disorders (e.g. psychosis), and skin infections or skin trauma (e.g. burns).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Further, electroacupuncture should be avoided at the spot of implanted electrical devices (such as pacemakers).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2011 systematic review of systematic reviews (internationally and without language restrictions) found that serious complications following acupuncture continue to be reported.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Between 2000 and 2009, ninety-five cases of serious adverse events, including five deaths, were reported.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Many such events are not inherent to acupuncture but are due to malpractice of acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] This might be why such complications have not been reported in surveys of adequately trained acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Most such reports originate from Asia, which may reflect the large number of treatments performed there or a relatively higher number of poorly trained Asian acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Many serious adverse events were reported from developed countries.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] These included Australia, Austria, Canada, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, the UK, and the US.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The number of adverse effects reported from the UK appears particularly unusual, which may indicate less under-reporting in the UK than other countries.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Reports included 38 cases of infections and 42 cases of organ trauma.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The most frequent adverse events included pneumothorax, and bacterial and viral infections.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2013 review found (without restrictions regarding publication date, study type or language) 295 cases of infections; mycobacterium was the pathogen in at least 96%.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Likely sources of infection include towels, hot packs or boiling tank water, and reusing reprocessed needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Possible sources of infection include contaminated needles, reusing personal needles, a person's skin containing mycobacterium, and reusing needles at various sites in the same person.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although acupuncture is generally considered a safe procedure, a 2013 review stated that the reports of infection transmission increased significantly in the prior decade, including those of mycobacterium.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although it is recommended that practitioners of acupuncture use disposable needles, the reuse of sterilized needles is still permitted.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It is also recommended that thorough control practices for preventing infection be implemented and adapted.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2013 systematic review of the English-language case reports found that serious adverse events associated with acupuncture are rare, but that acupuncture is not without risk.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Between 2000 and 2011 the English-language literature from 25 countries and regions reported 294 adverse events.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The majority of the reported adverse events were relatively minor, and the incidences were low.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] For example, a prospective survey of 34,000 acupuncture treatments found no serious adverse events and 43 minor ones, a rate of 1.3 per 1000 interventions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Another survey found there were 7.1% minor adverse events, of which 5 were serious, amid 97,733 acupuncture patients.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The most common adverse effect observed was infection (e.g. mycobacterium), and the majority of infections were bacterial in nature, caused by skin contact at the needling site.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Infection has also resulted from skin contact with unsterilized equipment or with dirty towels in an unhygienic clinical setting.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Adverse reactions from acupuncture, which are unusual and uncommon in typical acupuncture practice, included syncope, galactorrhoea, bilateral nystagmus, pyoderma gangrenosum, hepatotoxicity, eruptive lichen planus, and spontaneous needle migration.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2013 systematic review found 31 cases of vascular injuries caused by acupuncture, three causing death.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Two died from pericardial tamponade and one was from an aortoduodenal fistula.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The same review found vascular injuries were rare, bleeding and pseudoaneurysm were most prevalent.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2011 systematic review (without restriction in time or language), aiming to summarize all reported case of cardiac tamponade after acupuncture, found 26 cases resulting in 14 deaths, with little doubt about cause in most fatal instances.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The same review concluded that cardiac tamponade was a serious, usually fatal, though theoretically avoidable complication following acupuncture, and urged training to minimize risk.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2012 review found that a number of adverse events were reported after acupuncture in the UK's National Health Service (NHS), 95% of which were not severe, though miscategorization and under-reporting may alter the total figures.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] From January 2009 to December 2011, 468 safety incidents were recognized within the NHS organizations.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The adverse events recorded included retained needles (31%), dizziness (30%), loss of consciousness/unresponsive (19%), falls (4%), bruising or soreness at needle site (2%), pneumothorax (1%) and other adverse side effects (12%).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture practitioners should know, and be prepared to be responsible for, any substantial harm from treatments.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Some acupuncture proponents argue that the long history of acupuncture suggests it is safe.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] However, there is an increasing literature on adverse events (e.g. spinal-cord injury).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture seems to be safe in people getting anticoagulants, assuming needles are used at the correct location and depth, but studies are required to verify these findings.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Between 1980 and 2009, the Chinese-language literature reported 479 adverse events.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Prospective surveys show that mild, transient acupuncture-associated adverse events ranged from 6.71% to 15%.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In a study with 190,924 patients, the prevalence of serious adverse events was roughly 0.024%.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Another study showed a rate of adverse events requiring specific treatment of 2.2%, 4,963 incidences among 229,230 patients.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Infections, mainly hepatitis, after acupuncture are reported often in English-language research, though are rarely reported in Chinese-language research, making it plausible that acupuncture-associated infections have been underreported in China.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Infections were mostly caused by poor sterilization of acupuncture needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A causal link between acupuncture and the adverse events cardiac arrest, pyknolepsy, shock, fever, cough, thirst, aphonia, leg numbness, and sexual dysfunction remains uncertain.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The same review concluded that acupuncture can be considered inherently safe when practiced by properly trained practitioners, but the review also stated there is a need to find effective strategies to minimize the health risks.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Between 1999 and 2010, the Korean-language literature contained reports of 1104 adverse events.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Between the 1980s and 2002, the Japanese-language literature contained reports of 150 adverse events.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although acupuncture has been practiced for thousands of years in China, its use in pediatrics in the United States did not become common until the early 2000s.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In 2007, the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) conducted by the National Center For Health Statistics (NCHS) estimated that approximately 150,000 children had received acupuncture treatment for a variety of conditions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In 2008, a study determined that the use of acupuncture-needle treatment on children was "questionable" due to the possibility of adverse side-effects and the pain manifestation differences in children versus adults.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The study also includes warnings against practicing acupuncture on infants, as well as on children who are over-fatigued, very weak, or have over-eaten.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] When used on children, acupuncture is considered safe when administered by well-trained, licensed practitioners using sterile needles; however, a 2011 review found there was limited research to draw definite conclusions about the overall safety of pediatric acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The same review found 279 adverse events, 25 of them serious.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The adverse events were mostly mild in nature (e.g., bruising or bleeding).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The prevalence of mild adverse events ranged from 10.1% to 13.5%, an estimated 168 incidences among 1,422 patients.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] On rare occasions adverse events were serious (e.g. cardiac rupture or hemoptysis); many might have been a result of substandard practice.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The incidence of serious adverse events was 5 per one million, which included children and adults.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] When used during pregnancy, the majority of adverse events caused by acupuncture were mild and transient, with few serious adverse events.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The most frequent mild adverse event was needling or unspecified pain, followed by bleeding.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although two deaths (one stillbirth and one neonatal death) were reported, there was a lack of acupuncture-associated maternal mortality.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Limiting the evidence as certain, probable or possible in the causality evaluation, the estimated incidence of adverse events following acupuncture in pregnant women was 131 per 10,000.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Although acupuncture is not contraindicated in pregnant women, some specific acupuncture points are particularly sensitive to needle insertion; these spots, as well as the abdominal region, should be avoided during pregnancy.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Four adverse events associated with moxibustion were bruising, burns and cellulitis, spinal epidural abscess, and large superficial basal cell carcinoma.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Ten adverse events were associated with cupping.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The minor ones were keloid scarring, burns, and bullae; the serious ones were acquired hemophilia A, stroke following cupping on the back and neck, factitious panniculitis, reversible cardiac hypertrophy, and iron deficiency anemia.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] As with other alternative medicines, unethical or naïve practitioners may induce patients to exhaust financial resources by pursuing ineffective treatment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture is a substantial part of traditional Chinese medicine (TCM).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Early acupuncture beliefs relied on concepts that are common in TCM, such as a life force energy called *qi*.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] *Qi* was believed to flow from the body's primary organs (*zang-fu* organs) to the "superficial" body tissues of the skin, muscles, tendons, bones, and joints, through channels called meridians.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture points where needles are inserted are mainly (but not always) found at locations along the meridians.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture points not found along a meridian are called extraordinary points and those with no designated site are called *A-shi* points.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In TCM, disease is generally perceived as a disharmony or imbalance in energies such as yin, yang, *qi*, xuĕ, zàng-fǔ, meridians, and of the interaction between the body and the environment.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Therapy is based on which "pattern of disharmony" can be identified.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] For example, some diseases are believed to be caused by meridians being invaded with an excess of wind, cold, and damp.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] In order to determine which pattern is at hand, practitioners examine things like the color and shape of the tongue, the relative strength of pulse-points, the smell of the breath, the quality of breathing, or the sound of the voice.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] TCM and its concept of disease does not strongly differentiate between the cause and effect of symptoms.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Acupuncture was and is practiced differently by various Chinese philosophical schools, and differs from acupuncture from Korea and Japan.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Since its practice constantly evolved, it is hard to say that modern acupuncture points are based upon traditional acupuncture points, to the extent that modern acupuncture would have seemed heretical to ancient and medieval Chinese acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The standardization of the position of acupuncture points began in the 1950s.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Diachronic doxography shows that the positions of several major acupuncture points have changed, when comparing modern practice with a traditional textbook.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Traditional Chinese medicine does not reflect ancient medical practice, being instead a modern selection from very diverse traditions, "a minimal vestige of ideas and practices" having been retained from them.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Many within the scientific community consider acupuncture to be quackery and pseudoscience, having no effect other than as "theatrical placebo".
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] David Gorski has argued that of all forms of quackery, acupuncture has perhaps gained most acceptance among physicians and institutions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Academics Massimo Pigliucci and Maarten Boudry describe acupuncture as a "borderlands science" lying between science and pseudoscience.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2015 paper states that acupuncture is "often considered as 'pseudoscience' or 'quackery' with no credible or respectable place in medicine".
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] It is a generally held belief within the acupuncture community that acupuncture points and meridians structures are special conduits for electrical signals, but no research has established any consistent anatomical structure or function for either acupuncture points or meridians.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Human tests to determine whether electrical continuity was significantly different near meridians than other places in the body have been inconclusive.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Scientific research has not supported the existence of *qi*, meridians, or yin and yang.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A *Nature* editorial described TCM as "fraught with pseudoscience", with the majority of its treatments having no logical mechanism of action.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Quackwatch states that "TCM theory and practice are not based upon the body of knowledge related to health, disease, and health care that has been widely accepted by the scientific community.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] TCM practitioners disagree among themselves about how to diagnose patients and which treatments should go with which diagnoses.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Even if they could agree, the TCM theories are so nebulous that no amount of scientific study will enable TCM to offer rational care." Academic discussions of acupuncture still make reference to pseudoscientific concepts such as *qi* and meridians despite the lack of scientific evidence.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Some modern practitioners support the use of acupuncture to treat pain, but have abandoned the use of *qi*, meridians, *yin*, *yang* and other mystical energies as an explanatory frameworks.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The use of *qi* as an explanatory framework has been decreasing in China, even as it becomes more prominent during discussions of acupuncture in the US.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Many acupuncturists attribute pain relief to the release of endorphins when needles penetrate, but no longer support the idea that acupuncture can affect a disease.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Some studies suggest acupuncture causes a series of events within the central nervous system, and that it is possible to inhibit acupuncture's analgesic effects with the opioid antagonist compound naloxone, suggesting that the use of acupuncture may trigger the release of endogenous opioids.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] Mechanical deformation of the skin by acupuncture needles appears to result in the release of adenosine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] The anti-nociceptive effect of acupuncture may be mediated by the adenosine A1 receptor.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p01] A 2014 review in *Nature Reviews Cancer* analyzed mouse studies that suggested acupuncture relieves pain via the local release of adenosine, which then triggered nearby A1 receptors.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture, along with moxibustion, is one of the oldest practices of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Most historians believe the practice began in China, though there are some conflicting narratives on when it originated.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Academics David Ramey and Paul Buell said the exact date acupuncture was founded depends on the extent to which dating of ancient texts can be trusted and the interpretation of what constitutes acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupressure therapy was prevalent in India.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Once Buddhism spread to China, the acupressure therapy was also integrated into common medical practice in China and it came to be known as acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The major points of Indian acupressure and Chinese acupuncture are similar to each other.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to an article in *Rheumatology*, the first documentation of an "organized system of diagnosis and treatment" for acupuncture was in *Inner Classic of Huang Di* (Huangdi Neijing) from about 100 BC.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Gold and silver needles found in the tomb of Liu Sheng from around 100 BC are believed to be the earliest archaeological evidence of acupuncture, though it is unclear if that was their purpose.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to Plinio Prioreschi, the earliest known historical record of acupuncture is the Shiji ("Records of the Grand Historian"), written by a historian around 100 BC.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is believed that this text was documenting what was established practice at that time.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The 5,000-year-old mummified body of Ötzi the Iceman was found with 15 groups of tattoos, many of which were located at points on the body where acupuncture needles are used for abdominal or lower back problems.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Evidence from the body suggests Ötzi had these conditions.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] This has been cited as evidence that practices similar to acupuncture may have been practised elsewhere in Eurasia during the early Bronze Age; however, *The Oxford Handbook of the History of Medicine* calls this theory "speculative".
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is considered unlikely that acupuncture was practised before 2000 BC.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture may have been practised during the Neolithic era, near the end of the Stone Age, using sharpened stones called Bian shi.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Many Chinese texts from later eras refer to sharp stones called "plen", which means "stone probe", that may have been used for acupuncture purposes.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The ancient Chinese medical text, Huangdi Neijing, indicates that sharp stones were believed at-the-time to cure illnesses at or near the body's surface, perhaps because of the short depth a stone could penetrate.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] However, it is more likely that stones were used for other medical purposes, such as puncturing a growth to drain its pus.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The *Mawangdui* texts, which are believed to be from the 2nd century BC, mention the use of pointed stones to open abscesses, and moxibustion, but not for acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is also speculated that these stones may have been used for bloodletting, due to the ancient Chinese belief that illnesses were caused by demons within the body that could be killed or released.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is likely bloodletting was an antecedent to acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to historians Lu Gwei-djen and Joseph Needham, there is substantial evidence that acupuncture may have begun around 600 BC.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Some hieroglyphs and pictographs from that era suggests acupuncture and moxibustion were practised.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] However, historians Lu and Needham said it was unlikely a needle could be made out of the materials available in China during this time period.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is possible that bronze was used for early acupuncture needles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Tin, copper, gold and silver are also possibilities, though they are considered less likely, or to have been used in fewer cases.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] If acupuncture was practised during the Shang dynasty (1766 to 1122 BC), organic materials like thorns, sharpened bones, or bamboo may have been used.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Once methods for producing steel were discovered, it would replace all other materials, since it could be used to create a very fine, but sturdy needle.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Lu and Needham noted that all the ancient materials that could have been used for acupuncture and which often produce archaeological evidence, such as sharpened bones, bamboo or stones, were also used for other purposes.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] An article in *Rheumatology* said that the absence of any mention of acupuncture in documents found in the tomb of Mawangdui from 198 BC suggest that acupuncture was not practised by that time.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Several different and sometimes conflicting belief systems emerged regarding acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] This may have been the result of competing schools of thought.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Some ancient texts referred to using acupuncture to cause bleeding, while others mixed the ideas of blood-letting and spiritual qi energy.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Over time, the focus shifted from blood to the concept of puncturing specific points on the body, and eventually to balancing Yin and Yang energies as well.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to David Ramey, no single "method or theory" was ever predominantly adopted as the standard.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] At the time, scientific knowledge of medicine was not yet developed, especially because in China dissection of the deceased was forbidden, preventing the development of basic anatomical knowledge.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It is not certain when specific acupuncture points were introduced, but the autobiography of Bian Que from around 400–500 BC references inserting needles at designated areas.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Ramey and Buell said the "practice and theoretical underpinnings" of modern acupuncture were introduced in *The Yellow Emperor's Classic* (Huangdi Neijing) around 100 BC.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It introduced the concept of using acupuncture to manipulate the flow of life energy (*qi*) in a network of meridian (channels) in the body.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The network concept was made up of acu-tracts, such as a line down the arms, where it said acupoints were located.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Some of the sites acupuncturists use needles at today still have the same names as those given to them by the *Yellow Emperor's Classic*.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Numerous additional documents were published over the centuries introducing new acupoints.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By the 4th century AD, most of the acupuncture sites in use today had been named and identified.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In the first half of the 1st century AD, acupuncturists began promoting the belief that acupuncture's effectiveness was influenced by the time of day or night, the lunar cycle, and the season.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The 'science of the yin-yang cycles' (運氣學 *yùn qì xué*) was a set of beliefs that curing diseases relied on the alignment of both heavenly (*tian*) and earthly (*di*) forces that were attuned to cycles like that of the sun and moon.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] There were several different belief systems that relied on a number of celestial and earthly bodies or elements that rotated and only became aligned at certain times.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to Needham and Lu, these "arbitrary predictions" were depicted by acupuncturists in complex charts and through a set of special terminology.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture needles during this period were much thicker than most modern ones and often resulted in infection.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Infection is caused by a lack of sterilization, but at that time it was believed to be caused by use of the wrong needle, or needling in the wrong place, or at the wrong time.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Later, many needles were heated in boiling water, or in a flame.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Sometimes needles were used while they were still hot, creating a cauterizing effect at the injection site.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Nine needles were recommended in the *Great Compendium of Acupuncture and Moxibustion* from 1601, which may have been because of an ancient Chinese belief that nine was a magic number.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Other belief systems were based on the idea that the human body operated on a rhythm and acupuncture had to be applied at the right point in the rhythm to be effective.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In some cases a lack of balance between Yin and Yang were believed to be the cause of disease.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In the 1st century AD, many of the first books about acupuncture were published and recognized acupuncturist experts began to emerge.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The *Zhen Jiu Jia Yi Jing*, which was published in the mid-3rd century, became the oldest acupuncture book that is still in existence in the modern era.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Other books like the *Yu Gui Zhen Jing*, written by the Director of Medical Services for China, were also influential during this period, but were not preserved.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In the mid 7th century, Sun Simiao published acupuncture-related diagrams and charts that established standardized methods for finding acupuncture sites on people of different sizes and categorized acupuncture sites in a set of modules.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture became more established in China as improvements in paper led to the publication of more acupuncture books.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The Imperial Medical Service and the Imperial Medical College, which both supported acupuncture, became more established and created medical colleges in every province.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The public was also exposed to stories about royal figures being cured of their diseases by prominent acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By time the *Great Compendium of Acupuncture and Moxibustion* was published during the Ming dynasty (1368–1644 AD), most of the acupuncture practices used in the modern era had been established.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By the end of the Song dynasty (1279 AD), acupuncture had lost much of its status in China.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It became rarer in the following centuries, and was associated with less prestigious professions like alchemy, shamanism, midwifery and moxibustion.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Additionally, by the 18th century, scientific rationality was becoming more popular than traditional superstitious beliefs.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By 1757 a book documenting the history of Chinese medicine called acupuncture a "lost art".
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Its decline was attributed in part to the popularity of prescriptions and medications, as well as its association with the lower classes.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 1822, the Chinese Emperor signed a decree excluding the practice of acupuncture from the Imperial Medical Institute.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] He said it was unfit for practice by gentlemen-scholars.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In China acupuncture was increasingly associated with lower-class, illiterate practitioners.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It was restored for a time, but banned again in 1929 in favor of science-based medicine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Although acupuncture declined in China during this time period, it was also growing in popularity in other countries.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Korea is believed to be the first country in Asia that acupuncture spread to outside of China.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Within Korea there is a legend that acupuncture was developed by emperor Dangun, though it is more likely to have been brought into Korea from a Chinese colonial prefecture in 514 AD.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture use was commonplace in Korea by the 6th century.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It spread to Vietnam in the 8th and 9th centuries.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] As Vietnam began trading with Japan and China around the 9th century, it was influenced by their acupuncture practices as well.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] China and Korea sent "medical missionaries" that spread traditional Chinese medicine to Japan, starting around 219 AD.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 553, several Korean and Chinese citizens were appointed to re-organize medical education in Japan and they incorporated acupuncture as part of that system.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Japan later sent students back to China and established acupuncture as one of five divisions of the Chinese State Medical Administration System.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture began to spread to Europe in the second half of the 17th century.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Around this time, Willem ten Rhijne, a physician working for the Dutch East India Company, met Japanese acupuncture practitioners and later encouraged Europeans to further investigate it.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] He published the first in-depth description of acupuncture for the European audience and created the term "acupuncture" in his 1683 work *De Acupunctura*.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] France was an early adopter among the West due to the influence of Jesuit missionaries, who brought the practice to French clinics in the 16th century.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The French doctor Louis Berlioz (the father of the composer Hector Berlioz) is usually credited with being the first to experiment with the procedure in Europe in 1810, before publishing his findings in 1816.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By the 19th century, acupuncture had become commonplace in many areas of the world.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Americans and Britons began showing interest in acupuncture in the early 19th century, although interest waned by mid-century.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Western practitioners abandoned acupuncture's traditional beliefs in spiritual energy, pulse diagnosis, and the cycles of the moon, sun or the body's rhythm.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Diagrams of the flow of spiritual energy, for example, conflicted with the West's own anatomical diagrams.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It adopted a new set of ideas for acupuncture based on tapping needles into nerves.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Europe it was speculated that acupuncture may allow or prevent the flow of electricity in the body, as electrical pulses were found to make a frog's leg twitch after death.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The West eventually created a belief system based on Travell trigger points that were believed to inhibit pain.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] They were in the same locations as China's spiritually identified acupuncture points, but under a different nomenclature.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The first elaborate Western treatise on acupuncture was published in 1683 by Willem ten Rhijne.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In China, the popularity of acupuncture rebounded in 1949 when Mao Zedong took power and sought to unite China behind traditional cultural values.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It was also during this time that many Eastern medical practices were consolidated under the name traditional Chinese medicine (TCM).
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] New practices were adopted in the 20th century, such as using a cluster of needles, electrified needles, or leaving needles inserted for up to a week.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] A lot of emphasis developed on using acupuncture on the ear.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture research organizations such as the International Society of Acupuncture were founded in the 1940s and 1950s and acupuncture services became available in modern hospitals.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] China, where acupuncture was believed to have originated, was increasingly influenced by Western medicine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Meanwhile, acupuncture grew in popularity in the US.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The US Congress created the Office of Alternative Medicine in 1992 and the National Institutes of Health (NIH) declared support for acupuncture for some conditions in November 1997.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 1999, the National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine was created within the NIH.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture became the most popular alternative medicine in the US.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Politicians from the Chinese Communist Party said acupuncture was superstitious and conflicted with the party's commitment to science.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Communist Party Chairman Mao Zedong later reversed this position, arguing that the practice was based on scientific principles.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] During the Cultural Revolution, disbelief in acupuncture anesthesia was subjected to ruthless political repression.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 1971, *New York Times* reporter James Reston published an article on his acupuncture experiences in China, which led to more investigation of and support for acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The US President Richard Nixon visited China in 1972.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] During one part of the visit, the delegation was shown a patient undergoing major surgery while fully awake, ostensibly receiving acupuncture rather than anesthesia.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] One patient receiving open heart surgery while awake was ultimately found to have received a combination of three powerful sedatives as well as large injections of a local anesthetic into the wound.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] After the National Institute of Health expressed support for acupuncture for a limited number of conditions, adoption in the US grew further.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 1972 the first legal acupuncture center in the US was established in Washington DC and in 1973 the American Internal Revenue Service allowed acupuncture to be deducted as a medical expense.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Ronald Reagan, as the governor of California, vetoed a law which decriminalized acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 2006, a BBC documentary *Alternative Medicine* filmed a patient undergoing open heart surgery allegedly under acupuncture-induced anesthesia.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It was later revealed that the patient had been given a cocktail of anesthetics.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 2010, UNESCO inscribed "acupuncture and moxibustion of traditional Chinese medicine" on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List following China's nomination.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture is most heavily practiced in China and is popular in the US, Australia, and Europe.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Switzerland, acupuncture has become the most frequently used alternative medicine since 2004.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In the United Kingdom, a total of 4 million acupuncture treatments were administered in 2009.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Acupuncture is used in most pain clinics and hospices in the UK.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] An estimated 1 in 10 adults in Australia used acupuncture in 2004.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Japan, it is estimated that 25 percent of the population will try acupuncture at some point, though in most cases it is not covered by public health insurance.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Users of acupuncture in Japan are more likely to be elderly and to have a limited education.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Approximately half of users surveyed indicated a likelihood to seek such remedies in the future, while 37% did not.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Less than one percent of the US population reported having used acupuncture in the early 1990s.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] By the early 2010s, more than 14 million Americans reported having used acupuncture as part of their health care.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In the US, acupuncture is increasingly (as of 2014) used at academic medical centers, and is usually offered through CAM centers or anesthesia and pain management services.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Examples include those at Harvard University, Stanford University, Johns Hopkins University, and UCLA.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] CDC clinical practice guidelines from 2022 list acupuncture among the types of complementary and alternative medicines physicians should consider in preference to opioid prescription for certain kinds of pain.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The use of acupuncture in Germany increased by 20% in 2007, after the German acupuncture trials supported its efficacy for certain uses.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In 2011, there were more than one million users, and insurance companies have estimated that two-thirds of German users are women.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] As a result of the trials, German public health insurers began to cover acupuncture for chronic low back pain and osteoarthritis of the knee, but not tension headache or migraine.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] This decision was based in part on socio-political reasons.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Some insurers in Germany chose to stop reimbursement of acupuncture because of the trials.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] For other conditions, insurers in Germany were not convinced that acupuncture had adequate benefits over usual care or sham treatments.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Highlighting the results of the placebo group, researchers refused to accept a placebo therapy as efficient.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] According to Singh and Ernst "the WHO acupuncture panel did not include a single critic of acupuncture.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] There are various government and trade association regulatory bodies for acupuncture in the United Kingdom, the United States, Saudi Arabia, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, Canada, and in European countries and elsewhere.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The World Health Organization recommends that an acupuncturist receive 200 hours of specialized training if they are a physician and 2,500 hours for non-physicians before being licensed or certified; many governments have adopted similar standards.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Hong Kong, the practice of acupuncture is regulated by the Chinese Medicine Council, which was formed in 1999 by the Legislative Council.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] It includes a licensing exam, registration, and degree courses approved by the board.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Canada has acupuncture licensing programs in the provinces of British Columbia, Ontario, Alberta and Quebec; standards set by the Chinese Medicine and Acupuncture Association of Canada are used in provinces without government regulation.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Regulation in the US began in the 1970s in California, which was eventually followed by every state but Wyoming and Idaho.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] Licensing requirements vary greatly from state to state.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The needles used in acupuncture are regulated in the US by the Food and Drug Administration.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In some states acupuncture is regulated by a board of medical examiners, while in others by the board of licensing, health or education.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Japan, acupuncturists are licensed by the Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare after passing an examination and graduating from a technical school or university.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In Australia, the Chinese Medicine Board of Australia regulates acupuncture, among other Chinese medical traditions, and restricts the use of titles like 'acupuncturist' to registered practitioners only.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The practice of Acupuncture in New Zealand in 1990 acupuncture was included into the Governmental Accident Compensation Corporation (ACC) Act.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] This inclusion granted qualified and professionally registered acupuncturists the ability to provide subsidised care and treatment to citizens, residents, and temporary visitors for work- or sports-related injuries that occurred within the country of New Zealand.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] The two bodies for the regulation of acupuncture and attainment of ACC treatment provider status in New Zealand are Acupuncture NZ, and The New Zealand Acupuncture Standards Authority.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] At least 28 countries in Europe have professional associations for acupuncturists.
[src:national-health-service/acupuncture-p02] In France, the Académie Nationale de Médecine (National Academy of Medicine) has regulated acupuncture since 1955.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Some alternative practices are based on theories that contradict the established science of how the human body works; others appeal to the supernatural or superstitions to explain their effect or lack thereof.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In others, the practice has plausibility but lacks a positive risk–benefit outcome probability.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Research into alternative therapies often fails to follow proper research protocols (such as placebo-controlled trials, blind experiments and calculation of prior probability), providing invalid results.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] History has shown that if a method is proven to work, it eventually ceases to be alternative and becomes mainstream medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Much of the perceived effect of an alternative practice arises from a belief that it will be effective, the placebo effect, or from the treated condition resolving on its own (the natural course of disease).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] This is further exacerbated by the tendency to turn to alternative therapies upon the failure of medicine, at which point the condition will be at its worst and most likely to spontaneously improve.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the absence of this bias, especially for diseases that are not expected to get better by themselves such as cancer or HIV infection, multiple studies have shown significantly worse outcomes if patients turn to alternative therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] While this may be because these patients avoid effective treatment, some alternative therapies are actively harmful (such as cyanide poisoning from amygdalin, or the intentional ingestion of hydrogen peroxide) or actively interfere with effective treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The alternative medicine sector is a highly profitable industry with a strong lobby, and faces far less regulation over the use and marketing of unproven treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] **Complementary medicine** (**CM**), **complementary and alternative medicine** (**CAM**), **functional medicine** (**FM**), **integrated medicine** or **integrative medicine** (**IM**), and **holistic medicine** attempt to combine alternative practices with those of mainstream medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine practices become "alternative" when used outside their original settings and without proper scientific explanation and evidence.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative methods are often marketed as more "natural" or "holistic" than methods offered by medical science, that is sometimes derogatorily called "Big Pharma" by supporters of alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Billions of dollars have been spent studying alternative medicine, with few or no positive results and many methods thoroughly disproven.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Terminology has shifted over time, reflecting the preferred branding of practitioners.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Therapies are often framed as "natural" or "holistic", implicitly and intentionally suggesting that conventional medicine is "artificial" and "narrow in scope".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The meaning of the term "alternative" in the expression "alternative medicine", is not that it is an effective alternative to medical science (though some alternative medicine promoters may use the loose terminology to give the appearance of effectiveness).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biomedicine" or "medicine" is that part of medical science that applies principles of biology, physiology, molecular biology, biophysics, and other natural sciences to clinical practice, using scientific methods to establish the effectiveness of that practice.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Unlike medicine, an alternative product or practice does not originate from using scientific methods, but may instead be based on hearsay, religion, tradition, superstition, belief in supernatural energies, pseudoscience, errors in reasoning, propaganda, fraud, or other unscientific sources.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Some other definitions seek to specify alternative medicine in terms of its social and political marginality to mainstream healthcare.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] This can refer to the lack of support that alternative therapies receive from medical scientists regarding access to research funding, sympathetic coverage in the medical press, or inclusion in the standard medical curriculum.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, a widely used definition devised by the National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine (NCCIH) calls it "a group of diverse medical and health care systems, practices, and products that are not generally considered part of conventional medicine".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Some mainstream academic medical centers have integrative or functional medicine departments, including the Cleveland Clinic, the Mayo Clinic, Stanford University, UCLA, UC San Francisco and Northwestern University.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In contrast, other medical practitioners are unconvinced by these practices.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] For example, surgical oncologist, David Gorski has described integrative medicine as an attempt to bring pseudoscience into academic science-based medicine with skeptics such as Gorski and David Colquhoun referring to this with the pejorative term "quackademia".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Robert Todd Carroll described integrative medicine as "a synonym for 'alternative' medicine that, at its worst, integrates sense with nonsense.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] At its best, integrative medicine supports both consensus treatments of science-based medicine and treatments that the science, while promising perhaps, does not justify." Rose Shapiro has criticized the field of alternative medicine for rebranding the same practices as integrative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] CAM is an acronym for *complementary and alternative medicine*.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine (FM) is a form of alternative medicine that encompasses many unproven and disproven methods and treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] It is a rebranding of complementary and alternative medicine (CAM), and as such is pseudoscientific, and has been described as a form of quackery.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the US, FM practices have been ruled ineligible for course credits by the American Academy of Family Physicians because of concerns they may be harmful.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Functional medicine was created by Jeffrey Bland, who founded The Institute for Functional Medicine (IFM), which is based in the US state of Washington, in the early 1990s as part of one of his companies, HealthComm.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] IFM, which promotes functional medicine, became a registered non-profit in 2001.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Mark Hyman became an IFM board member and prominent promoter.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski, a surgical oncologist at Wayne State University, has written that FM is not well-defined and performs "expensive and generally unnecessary tests".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Gorski says FM's vagueness is a deliberate tactic that makes functional medicine difficult to challenge.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] These are meant to correspond to the underlying causes of health issues, the immediate causes, and the particular characteristics of a person's illness.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] A functional medicine practitioner devises a "matrix" from these factors to serve as the basis for treatment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Treatments, practices, and concepts are generally not supported by medical evidence.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Patients of functional medicine practitioners may also be told to undertake unnecessary diets that can limit food choices.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1990s, integrative medicine started to be marketed by a new term, "functional medicine".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] FM practitioners claim to diagnose and treat conditions that have been found by research studies not to exist, such as adrenal fatigue and numerous imbalances in body chemistry.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] For instance, contrary to scientific evidence, Joe Pizzorno, a major figure in FM, claimed that 25% of people in the United States have heavy metal poisoning and need to undergo detoxification.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Many scientists state that such detox supplements are a waste of time and money.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Detox has been also called "mass delusion".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2014, the American Academy of Family Physicians withdrew course credits for functional medicine courses, having identified some of its treatments as "harmful and dangerous".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2018, it partly lifted the ban, but only to allow overview classes, not to teach its practice.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The opening of centers for functional medicine at the Cleveland Clinic and George Washington University was described by David Gorski as an "unfortunate" example of "quackademia" — that is, a quackery infiltrating academic medical centers.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Traditional medicine (TM) refers to certain practices within a culture which have existed since before the advent of medical science, Many TM practices are based on "holistic" approaches to disease and health, versus the scientific evidence-based methods in conventional medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Others say that alternative medicine cannot be precisely defined because of the diversity of theories and practices it includes, and because the boundaries between alternative and conventional medicine overlap, are porous, and change.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Healthcare practices categorized as alternative may differ in their historical origin, theoretical basis, diagnostic technique, therapeutic practice and in their relationship to the medical mainstream.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Under a definition of alternative medicine as "non-mainstream", treatments considered alternative in one location may be considered conventional in another.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] There's only medicine that works and medicine that doesn't.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine consists of a wide range of health care practices, products, and therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The shared feature is a claim to heal that is not based on the scientific method.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices are diverse in their foundations and methodologies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine practices may be classified by their cultural origins or by the types of beliefs upon which they are based.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Different cultures may have their own unique traditional or belief based practices developed recently or over thousands of years, and specific practices or entire systems of practices.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medicine, such as using naturopathy or homeopathy in place of conventional medicine, is based on belief systems not grounded in science.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative medical systems may be based on traditional medicine practices, such as traditional Chinese medicine (TCM), Ayurveda in India, or practices of other cultures around the world.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Some useful applications of traditional medicines have been researched and accepted within ordinary medicine, however the underlying belief systems are seldom scientific and are not accepted.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Bases of belief may include belief in existence of supernatural energies undetected by the science of physics, as in biofields, or in belief in properties of the energies of physics that are inconsistent with the laws of physics, as in energy medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Substance based practices use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, non-vitamin supplements and megavitamins, animal and fungal products, and minerals, including use of these products in traditional medical practices that may also incorporate other methods.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Examples include healing claims for non-vitamin supplements, fish oil, Omega-3 fatty acid, glucosamine, echinacea, flaxseed oil, and ginseng.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Herbal medicine, or phytotherapy, includes not just the use of plant products, but may also include the use of animal and mineral products.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] It is among the most commercially successful branches of alternative medicine, and includes the tablets, powders and elixirs that are sold as "nutritional supplements".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Only a very small percentage of these have been shown to have any efficacy, and there is little regulation as to standards and safety of their contents.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The United States agency National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health (NCCIH) has created a classification system for branches of complementary and alternative medicine that divides them into five major groups.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] These groups have some overlap, and distinguish two types of energy medicine: *veritable* which involves scientifically observable energy (including magnet therapy, colorpuncture and light therapy) and *putative*, which invokes physically undetectable or unverifiable energy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] None of these energies have any evidence to support that they affect the body in any positive or health promoting way.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Mind-body interventions: Explore the interconnection between the mind, body, and spirit, under the premise that they affect "bodily functions and symptoms".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] A connection between mind and body is conventional medical fact, and this classification does not include therapies with proven function such as cognitive behavioral therapy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] "Biology"-based practices: Use substances found in nature such as herbs, foods, vitamins, and other natural substances.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] (As used here, "biology" does *not* refer to the science of biology, but is a usage newly coined by NCCIH in the primary source used for this article.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Manipulative and body-based practices: feature manipulation or movement of body parts, such as is done in bodywork, chiropractic, and osteopathic manipulation.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] It includes the histories of complementary medicine and of integrative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Before the 1970s, western practitioners that were not part of the increasingly science-based medical establishment were referred to "irregular practitioners", and were dismissed by the medical establishment as unscientific and as practicing quackery.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Until the 1970s, irregular practice became increasingly marginalized as quackery and fraud, as western medicine increasingly incorporated scientific methods and discoveries, and had a corresponding increase in success of its treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 1970s, irregular practices were grouped with traditional practices of nonwestern cultures and with other unproven or disproven practices that were not part of biomedicine, with the entire group collectively marketed and promoted under the single expression "alternative medicine".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of alternative medicine in the west began to rise following the counterculture movement of the 1960s, as part of the rising new age movement of the 1970s.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] At the same time, in 1975, the American Medical Association, which played the central role in fighting quackery in the United States, abolished its quackery committee and closed down its Department of Investigation.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] By the early to mid 1970s the expression "alternative medicine" came into widespread use, and the expression became mass marketed as a collection of "natural" and effective treatment "alternatives" to science-based biomedicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Changes included relaxed medical licensing, the development of managed care, rising consumerism, and the establishment of the USA Office of Alternative Medicine (later National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine, currently National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Mainly as a result of reforms following the Flexner Report of 1910 medical education in established medical schools in the US has generally not included alternative medicine as a teaching topic.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Typically, their teaching is based on current practice and scientific knowledge about: anatomy, physiology, histology, embryology, neuroanatomy, pathology, pharmacology, microbiology and immunology.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools' teaching includes such topics as doctor-patient communication, ethics, the art of medicine, and engaging in complex clinical reasoning (medical decision-making).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Writing in 2002, Snyderman and Weil remarked that by the early twentieth century the Flexner model had helped to create the 20th-century academic health center, in which education, research, and practice were inseparable.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] By 2001 some form of CAM training was being offered by at least 75 out of 125 medical schools in the US.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Exceptionally, the School of Medicine of the University of Maryland, Baltimore, includes a research institute for integrative medicine (a member entity of the Cochrane Collaboration).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Medical schools are responsible for conferring medical degrees, but a physician typically may not legally practice medicine until licensed by the local government authority.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Licensed physicians in the US who have attended one of the established medical schools there have usually graduated Doctor of Medicine (MD).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] All states require that applicants for MD licensure be graduates of an approved medical school and complete the United States Medical Licensing Examination (USMLE).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] There is a general scientific consensus that alternative therapies lack the requisite scientific validation, and their effectiveness is either unproved or disproved.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Many of the claims regarding the efficacy of alternative medicines are controversial, since research on them is frequently of low quality and methodologically flawed.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Selective publication bias, marked differences in product quality and standardisation, and some companies making unsubstantiated claims call into question the claims of efficacy of isolated examples where there is evidence for alternative therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In 2003, a project funded by the CDC identified 208 condition-treatment pairs, of which 58% had been studied by at least one randomized controlled trial (RCT), and 23% had been assessed with a meta-analysis.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] According to a 2005 book by a US Institute of Medicine panel, the number of RCTs focused on CAM has risen dramatically.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] As of 2005, the Cochrane Library had 145 CAM-related Cochrane systematic reviews and 340 non-Cochrane systematic reviews.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] An analysis of the conclusions of only the 145 Cochrane reviews was done by two readers.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In 83% of the cases, the readers agreed.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the 17% in which they disagreed, a third reader agreed with one of the initial readers to set a rating.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] These studies found that, for CAM, 38.4% concluded positive effect or possibly positive (12.4%), 4.8% concluded no effect, 0.7% concluded harmful effect, and 56.6% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] An assessment of conventional treatments found that 41.3% concluded positive or possibly positive effect, 20% concluded no effect, 8.1% concluded net harmful effects, and 21.3% concluded insufficient evidence.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] However, the CAM review used the more developed 2004 Cochrane database, while the conventional review used the initial 1998 Cochrane database.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Alternative therapies do not "complement" (improve the effect of, or mitigate the side effects of) functional medical treatment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Significant drug interactions caused by alternative therapies may instead negatively impact functional treatment by making prescription drugs less effective, such as interference by herbal preparations with warfarin.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In the same way as for conventional therapies, drugs, and interventions, it can be difficult to test the efficacy of alternative medicine in clinical trials.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In instances where an established, effective, treatment for a condition is already available, the Helsinki Declaration states that withholding such treatment is unethical in most circumstances.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Use of standard-of-care treatment in addition to an alternative technique being tested may produce confounded or difficult-to-interpret results.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Anything classified as alternative medicine by definition does not have a proven healing or medical effect.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] However, there are different mechanisms through which it can be perceived to "work".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The common denominator of these mechanisms is that effects are mis-attributed to the alternative treatment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] A placebo is a treatment with no intended therapeutic value.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] An example of a placebo is an inert pill, but it can include more dramatic interventions like sham surgery.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The *placebo effect* is the concept that patients will perceive an improvement after being treated with an inert treatment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The opposite of the placebo effect is the *nocebo effect*, when patients who expect a treatment to be harmful will perceive harmful effects after taking it.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Placebos do not have a physical effect on diseases or improve overall outcomes, but patients may report improvements in subjective outcomes such as pain and nausea.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] A 1955 study suggested that a substantial part of a medicine's impact was due to the placebo effect.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] However, reassessments found the study to have flawed methodology.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] This and other modern reviews suggest that other factors like natural recovery and reporting bias should also be considered.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] All of these are reasons why alternative therapies may be credited for improving a patient's condition even though the objective effect is non-existent, or even harmful.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] David Gorski argues that alternative treatments should be treated as a placebo, rather than as medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Almost none have performed significantly better than a placebo in clinical trials.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Furthermore, distrust of conventional medicine may lead to patients experiencing the nocebo effect when taking effective medication.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] A patient who receives an inert treatment may report improvements afterwards that it did not cause.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] Assuming it was the cause without evidence is an example of the regression fallacy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] This may be due to a natural recovery from the illness, or a fluctuation in the symptoms of a long-term condition.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] The concept of regression toward the mean implies that an extreme result is more likely to be followed by a less extreme result.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] There are also reasons why a placebo treatment group may outperform a "no-treatment" group in a test which are not related to a patient's experience.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] These include patients reporting more favourable results than they really felt due to politeness or "experimental subordination", observer bias, and misleading wording of questions.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p01] In their 2010 systematic review of studies into placebos, Asbjørn Hróbjartsson and Peter C.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of complementary medicine usually discuss and advise patients as to available alternative therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients often express interest in mind-body complementary therapies because they offer a non-drug approach to treating some health conditions.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In a 2018 interview with *The BMJ*, Edzard Ernst stated: "The present popularity of complementary and alternative medicine is also inviting criticism of what we are doing in mainstream medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] It shows that we aren't fulfilling a certain need-we are not giving patients enough time, compassion, or empathy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] These are things that complementary practitioners are very good at.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is a profitable industry with large media advertising expenditures.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Accordingly, alternative practices are often portrayed positively and compared favorably to "big pharma".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Paul Offit proposed that "alternative medicine becomes quackery" in four ways: by recommending against conventional therapies that are helpful, promoting potentially harmful therapies without adequate warning, draining patients' bank accounts, or by promoting "magical thinking".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Promoting alternative medicine has been called dangerous and unethical.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Authors have speculated on the socio-cultural and psychological reasons for the appeal of alternative medicines among the minority using them *in lieu* of conventional medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] There are several socio-cultural reasons for the interest in these treatments centered on the low level of scientific literacy among the public at large and a concomitant increase in antiscientific attitudes and new age mysticism.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Related to this are vigorous marketing of extravagant claims by the alternative medical community combined with inadequate media scrutiny and attacks on critics.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine is criticized for taking advantage of the least fortunate members of society.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Many patients lack access to contemporary medicine, due to a lack of private or public health insurance, which leads them to seek out lower-cost alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Medical doctors are also aggressively marketing alternative medicine to profit from this market.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Patients can be averse to the painful, unpleasant, and sometimes-dangerous side effects of biomedical treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Treatments for severe diseases such as cancer and HIV infection have well-known, significant side-effects.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Even low-risk medications such as antibiotics can have potential to cause life-threatening anaphylactic reactions in a very few individuals.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Many medications may cause minor but bothersome symptoms such as cough or upset stomach.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In all of these cases, patients may be seeking out alternative therapies to avoid the adverse effects of conventional treatments.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] According to research published in 2015, the increasing popularity of CAM needs to be explained by moral convictions or lifestyle choices rather than by economic reasoning.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In developing nations, access to essential medicines is severely restricted by lack of resources and poverty.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Traditional remedies, often closely resembling or forming the basis for alternative remedies, may comprise primary healthcare or be integrated into the healthcare system.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In Africa, traditional medicine is used for 80% of primary healthcare, and in developing nations as a whole over one-third of the population lack access to essential medicines.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In Latin America, inequities against BIPOC communities keep them tied to their traditional practices and therefore, it is often these communities that constitute the majority of users of alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Racist attitudes towards certain communities disable them from accessing more urbanized modes of care.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In a study that assessed access to care in rural communities of Latin America, it was found that discrimination is a huge barrier to the ability of citizens to access care; more specifically, women of Indigenous and African descent, and lower-income families were especially hurt.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Such exclusion exacerbates the inequities that minorities in Latin America already face.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Consistently excluded from many systems of westernized care for socioeconomic and other reasons, low-income communities of color often turn to traditional medicine for care as it has proved reliable to them across generations.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Commentators including David Horrobin have proposed adopting a prize system to reward medical research.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] This stands in opposition to the current mechanism for funding research proposals in most countries around the world.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In the US, the NCCIH provides public research funding for alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The NCCIH has spent more than US$2.5 billion on such research since 1992 and this research has not demonstrated the efficacy of alternative therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] As of 2011, the NCCIH's sister organization in the NIH Office of Cancer Complementary and Alternative Medicine had given out grants of around $105 million each year for several years.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Testing alternative medicine that has no scientific basis (as in the aforementioned grants) has been called a waste of scarce research resources.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] That alternative medicine has been on the rise "in countries where Western science and scientific method generally are accepted as the major foundations for healthcare, and 'evidence-based' practice is the dominant paradigm" was described as an "enigma" in the *Medical Journal of Australia*.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] A 15-year systematic review published in 2022 on the global acceptance and use of CAM among medical specialists found the overall acceptance of CAM at 52% and the overall use at 45%.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In the United States, the 1974 Child Abuse Prevention and Treatment Act (CAPTA) required that for states to receive federal money, they had to grant religious exemptions to child neglect and abuse laws regarding religion-based healing practices.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Thirty-one states have child-abuse religious exemptions.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The use of alternative medicine in the US has increased, with a 50 percent increase in expenditures and a 25 percent increase in the use of alternative therapies between 1990 and 1997 in America.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] According to a national survey conducted in 2002, "36 percent of U.S. adults aged 18 years and over use some form of complementary and alternative medicine." Americans spend many billions on the therapies annually.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Most Americans used CAM to treat and/or prevent musculoskeletal conditions or other conditions associated with chronic or recurring pain.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In America, women were more likely than men to use CAM, with the biggest difference in use of mind-body therapies including prayer specifically for health reasons".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2008, more than 37% of American hospitals offered alternative therapies, up from 27 percent in 2005, and 25% in 2004.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] More than 70% of the hospitals offering CAM were in urban areas.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] A survey of Americans found that 88 percent thought that "there are some good ways of treating sickness that medical science does not recognize".
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Use of magnets was the most common tool in energy medicine in America, and among users of it, 58 percent described it as at least "sort of scientific", when it is not at all scientific.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In 2002, at least 60 percent of US medical schools have at least some class time spent teaching alternative therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] "Therapeutic touch" was taught at more than 100 colleges and universities in 75 countries before the practice was debunked by a nine-year-old child for a school science project.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The most common CAM therapies used in the US in 2002 were prayer (45%), herbalism (19%), breathing meditation (12%), meditation (8%), chiropractic medicine (8%), yoga (5–6%), body work (5%), diet-based therapy (4%), progressive relaxation (3%), mega-vitamin therapy (3%) and visualization (2%).
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In Britain, the most often used alternative therapies were Alexander technique, aromatherapy, Bach and other flower remedies, body work therapies including massage, Counseling stress therapies, hypnotherapy, meditation, reflexology, Shiatsu, Ayurvedic medicine, nutritional medicine, and yoga.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Ayurvedic medicine remedies are mainly plant based with some use of animal materials.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Safety concerns include the use of herbs containing toxic compounds and the lack of quality control in Ayurvedic facilities.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] According to the National Health Service (England), the most commonly used complementary and alternative medicines (CAM) supported by the NHS in the UK are: acupuncture, aromatherapy, chiropractic, homeopathy, massage, osteopathy and clinical hypnotherapy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary therapies are often used in palliative care or by practitioners attempting to manage chronic pain in patients.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Integrative medicine is considered more acceptable in the interdisciplinary approach used in palliative care than in other areas of medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] "From its early experiences of care for the dying, palliative care took for granted the necessity of placing patient values and lifestyle habits at the core of any design and delivery of quality care at the end of life.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The alternative medicine lobby has successfully pushed for alternative therapies to be subject to far less regulation than conventional medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Some professions of complementary/traditional/alternative medicine, such as chiropractic, have achieved full regulation in North America and other parts of the world and are regulated in a manner similar to that governing science-based medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In contrast, other approaches may be partially recognized and others have no regulation at all.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In some cases, promotion of alternative therapies is allowed when there is demonstrably no effect, only a tradition of use.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Despite laws making it illegal to market or promote alternative therapies for use in cancer treatment, many practitioners promote them.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Regulation and licensing of alternative medicine ranges widely from country to country, and state to state.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In Austria and Germany complementary and alternative medicine is mainly in the hands of doctors with MDs, and half or more of the American alternative practitioners are licensed MDs.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In Germany herbs are tightly regulated: half are prescribed by doctors and covered by health insurance.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Government bodies in the US and elsewhere have published information or guidance about alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), has issued online warnings for consumers about medication health fraud.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] This includes a section on Alternative Medicine Fraud, such as a warning that Ayurvedic products generally have not been approved by the FDA before marketing.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The National Science Foundation has studied the problematic side of the public's attitudes and understandings of science fiction, pseudoscience, and belief in alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Forms of alternative medicine that are biologically active can be dangerous even when used in conjunction with conventional medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Examples include immuno-augmentation therapy, shark cartilage, bioresonance therapy, oxygen and ozone therapies, and insulin potentiation therapy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Some herbal remedies can cause dangerous interactions with chemotherapy drugs, radiation therapy, or anesthetics during surgery, among other problems.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Conventional treatments are subjected to testing for undesired side-effects, whereas alternative therapies, in general, are not subjected to such testing at all.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Any treatment – whether conventional or alternative – that has a biological or psychological effect on a patient may also have potential to possess dangerous biological or psychological side-effects.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] An exception to the normal thinking regarding side-effects is homeopathy.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may discourage people from getting the best possible treatment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Those having experienced or perceived success with one alternative therapy for a minor ailment may be convinced of its efficacy and persuaded to extrapolate that success to some other alternative therapy for a more serious, possibly life-threatening illness.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] For this reason, critics argue that therapies that rely on the placebo effect to define success are very dangerous.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] According to mental health journalist Scott Lilienfeld in 2002, "unvalidated or scientifically unsupported mental health practices can lead individuals to forgo effective treatments" and refers to this as opportunity cost.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Individuals who spend large amounts of time and money on ineffective treatments may be left with precious little of either, and may forfeit the opportunity to obtain treatments that could be more helpful.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In short, even innocuous treatments can indirectly produce negative outcomes.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Between 2001 and 2003, four children died in Australia because their parents chose ineffective naturopathic, homeopathic, or other alternative medicines and diets rather than conventional therapies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] There have always been "many therapies offered outside of conventional cancer treatment centers and based on theories not found in biomedicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Complementary and alternative medicine (CAM) is not as well researched as conventional medicine, which undergoes intense research before release to the public.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Practitioners of science-based medicine also discard practices and treatments when they are shown ineffective, while alternative practitioners do not.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Funding for research is also sparse making it difficult to do further research for effectiveness of CAM.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Most funding for CAM is funded by government agencies.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Proposed research for CAM are rejected by most private funding agencies because the results of research are not reliable.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] The research for CAM has to meet certain standards from research ethics committees, which most CAM researchers find almost impossible to meet.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Even with the little research done on it, CAM has not been proven to be effective.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Studies that have been done will be cited by CAM practitioners in an attempt to claim a basis in science.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] These studies tend to have a variety of problems, such as small samples, various biases, poor research design, lack of controls, negative results, etc.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Even those with positive results can be better explained as resulting in false positives due to bias and noisy data.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Alternative medicine may lead to a false understanding of the body and of the process of science.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] It is possible for a method to change categories (proven vs. unproven), based on increased knowledge of its effectiveness or lack thereof.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Prominent supporters of this position are George D.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Lundberg, former editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* (*JAMA*) and the journal's interim editor-in-chief Phil Fontanarosa.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Writing in 1999 in *CA: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians* Barrie R.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Cassileth mentioned a 1997 letter to the United States Senate's Subcommittee on Public Health and Safety, which had deplored the lack of critical thinking and scientific rigor in OAM-supported research, had been signed by four Nobel Laureates and other prominent scientists.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Sampson has also pointed out that CAM tolerated contradiction without thorough reason and experiment.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett has pointed out that there is a policy at the NIH of never saying something does not work, only that a different version or dose might give different results.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Barrett also expressed concern that, just because some "alternatives" have merit, there is the impression that the rest deserve equal consideration and respect even though most are worthless, since they are all classified under the one heading of alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Many alternative medical treatments are not patentable, which may lead to less research funding from the private sector.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In addition, in most countries, alternative therapies (in contrast to pharmaceuticals) can be marketed without any proof of efficacy – also a disincentive for manufacturers to fund scientific research.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is also often less regulated than conventional medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] There are ethical concerns about whether people who perform CAM have the proper knowledge to treat patients.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] CAM is often done by non-physicians who do not operate with the same medical licensing laws which govern conventional medicine, and it is often described as an issue of non-maleficence.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] According to two writers, Wallace Sampson and K.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Butler, marketing is part of the training required in alternative medicine, and propaganda methods in alternative medicine have been traced back to those used by Hitler and Goebbels in their promotion of pseudoscience in medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] In November 2011 Edzard Ernst stated that the "level of misinformation about alternative medicine has now reached the point where it has become dangerous and unethical.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] So far, alternative medicine has remained an ethics-free zone.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Some commentators have said that special consideration must be given to the issue of conflicts of interest in alternative medicine.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Edzard Ernst has said that most researchers into alternative medicine are at risk of "unidirectional bias" because of a generally uncritical belief in their chosen subject.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Ernst cites as evidence the phenomenon whereby 100% of a sample of acupuncture trials originating in China had positive conclusions.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] David Gorski contrasts evidence-based medicine, in which researchers try to disprove hyphotheses, with what he says is the frequent practice in pseudoscience-based research, of striving to confirm pre-existing notions.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Research into alternative therapies has been criticized for "diverting research time, money, and other resources from more fruitful lines of investigation in order to pursue a theory that has no basis in biology." Research methods expert and author of *Snake Oil Science*, R.
[src:national-health-service/alternative-medicine-p02] Barker Bausell, has stated that "it's become politically correct to investigate nonsense." A commonly cited statistic is that the US National Institute of Health had spent $2.5 billion on investigating alternative therapies prior to 2009, with none being found to be effective.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Raised in Monmouthshire, in modern day Blaenau Gwent, by a Welsh working-class family, he was the son of a coal miner and left school at 14.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan first worked as a miner during his teens where he became involved in local miners' union politics.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was elected head of his Miners' Lodge when aged 19, where he frequently railed against management.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He joined the Labour Party and attended Central Labour College in London.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] On his return to South Wales he struggled to find work, remaining unemployed for nearly three years before gaining employment as a union official, which led to him becoming a leading figure in the 1926 general strike.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1928, Bevan won a seat on Monmouthshire County Council and he was elected as the MP for Ebbw Vale the following year.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In Parliament, he became a vocal critic of numerous other politicians from all parties, particularly Winston Churchill and David Lloyd George.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] After the war, Bevan was chosen as the Minister of Health in Clement Attlee's new Labour government, becoming the youngest member of the cabinet at 47, with his remit also including housing.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Inspired by the Tredegar Medical Aid Society in his hometown in South Wales, Bevan led the campaign for a National Health Service to provide medical care free at point-of-need across the UK, regardless of wealth.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Despite resistance from opposition parties and the British Medical Association, the National Health Service Act 1946 was passed and launched in 1948, nationalising more than 2,500 hospitals within the United Kingdom.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was named Minister of Labour in 1951, but resigned after two months in office, when the Attlee government proposed the introduction of prescription charges for dental and vision care and decided to transfer funds from the National Insurance Fund to pay for rearmament.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His influence waned after his departure, although a left-wing group within the party became known as "Bevanites".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Attlee and Labour were ousted from power in a snap election held six months after Bevan's resignation, but Attlee continued on as Labour Party Leader.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] When Attlee retired from the leadership in 1955, Bevan unsuccessfully contested the party leadership with Hugh Gaitskell, but was appointed Shadow Colonial Secretary and later Shadow Foreign Secretary.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1959, he was elected Deputy Leader of the Labour Party and held the post for a year until his death in 1960 from stomach cancer, at the age of 62.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His death led to "an outpouring of national mourning".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 2004, more than 44 years after his death, he was voted first in a list of 100 Welsh Heroes, having been credited for his contribution to the founding of the welfare state in the UK.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Aneurin Bevan was born on 15 November 1897 at 32 Charles Street in Tredegar, Monmouthshire, a working-class mining town, where an estimated 90 per cent of the town's inhabitants relied on the local mines for employment.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The town was situated in the South Wales Valleys and was on the northern edge of the South Wales coalfield.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was the son of coal miner David Bevan and Phoebe (née Prothero), a seamstress.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] David Bevan was born in Tredegar but his family had originally hailed from Carmarthenshire, and he followed his own father into the mines, starting work at 5:30am each day and returning home late in the evening.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was adept at construction and added several modern features when the family moved to 7 Charles Street, installing the first gas stove in the street, an inside toilet and running hot water.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Both Bevan's parents were Nonconformists: his father was a Baptist and his mother a Methodist, although he became an atheist.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was converted to socialism by the writings of Robert Blatchford in *The Clarion* and began attending meetings of the Independent Labour Party following the founding of its branch in Tredegar.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] It was around this time that he first "reject[ed] his chapel upbringing" and became an atheist.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was a member of the Honourable Society of Cymmrodorion and wrote his own poems, one of which won an inter-chapel eisteddfod.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Aneurin's mother was also from Tredegar, but had English roots: her grandfather was from Hereford.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan's maternal grandfather John was a blacksmith who had moved to Tredegar from Hay-on-Wye to work in the Bedwellty mines.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The couple had ten children altogether—six boys and four girls—although four died in infancy and one died at the age of eight.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Aneurin Bevan attended Sirhowy Elementary School, where he achieved little.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He developed a severe stammer as a child and, according to his younger sister Myfanwy, became "a lonely chap", due to the need to shy away from the attention it brought him.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His father died by pneumoconiosis (a lung condition caused by long term inhalation of coal dust) but no compensation was paid to him, as it was not classed as an industrial disease under the Workmen's Compensation Act.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] At the age of 13, in his last months of schooling, he worked as a butcher's boy at a local store.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He worked at the butcher's for several months before leaving school, instead working in the local Ty-Trist Colliery.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] There he earned around ten shillings per week with most going to his parents to help support the family.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He began attending fortnightly meetings of the local Plebs' League where he studied, among other things, Marxism.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan also joined the Tredegar branch of the South Wales Miners' Federation and became a trade union activist: he was head of his local Miners' Lodge at 19 years of age.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was called up for service during the First World War, and was briefly arrested when his sister Blodwen burnt his conscription papers and he failed to report for duty.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan appeared in court but was cleared when he produced confirmation that he suffered from nystagmus.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan became a well-known local orator and was seen by his employers, the Tredegar Iron and Coal Company, as a troublemaker.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The manager of the colliery found an excuse to get him dismissed.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] With the support of the Miners' Federation, the case was judged as one of victimisation and the company was forced to re-employ him.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He and his brother Billy did eventually leave Ty-Tryst and worked at the Bedwellty pit, but were forced to move again after a disagreement with the site's deputy manager over Bevan reporting information to the miner's inspector.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The pair went to work at Whitworth Colliery, but fell foul of management when Bevan refused to use cheaper second-hand timber as he deemed it unsafe.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was later fired for refusing to unload, and successfully challenged the motion but was moved to Pochin, generally considered a punishment due to the poor site conditions.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] 1919 saw the foundation of the Tredegar Labour Party and Bevan was selected as one of four Labour delegates to contest the West Ward in the Tredegar Urban District election.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Although he was defeated, he gained attention from his peers and he won a scholarship to the Central Labour College in London, sponsored by the South Wales Miners' Federation.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] There, he spent two years studying economics, politics and history.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He read Marxism at the college and was a brief follower of Noah Ablett, developing his left-wing political outlook.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Reciting long passages by William Morris with the help of an elocution tutor, Bevan gradually began to overcome the stammer that he had since childhood.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan remained at the college until 1921, attending at a time when a number of his contemporaries from South Wales, including Jim Griffiths, were also students at the college.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Some historians have questioned how influential the college was on his political development.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was not, apparently, one of the most diligent students, and found it difficult to follow an organised routine, including arising early for breakfast.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was one of the founding members of the "Query Club" with his brother Billy and Walter Conway.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Conway was a local miner who had been elected to the Bedwellty Board of Guardians and offered Bevan advice on overcoming his stammer, stating "if you can't say it, you don't know it".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan followed his advice, often practising his speeches to his friends to perfect his speech and wording, and remarked that Conway's words were the "best advice I ever had".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The Query club started in 1920 or 1921 and they met in Tredegar.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] They would collect money weekly for any member who needed it.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The club intended to break the hold that the Tredegar Iron and Coal Company had on the town by becoming members of pivotal groups in the community.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Upon returning home in 1921, he found that the Tredegar Iron and Coal Company refused to re-employ him.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan ended up in a fist fight with a group of miners who refused to strike over his rejection.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Apart from a six-week period as a labourer for Tredegar Council, he did not find work until 1924 and his employer, the Bedwellty Colliery, closed down ten months later.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan then endured another year of unemployment, the family surviving on his sister's wages, when his unemployment benefit was stopped due to her income, and his father's sick pay.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In February 1925, his father died of pneumoconiosis, an illness caused by the inhalation of coal dust.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1926 he found work as a paid union official.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His wage of £5 a week was paid by the members of the local Miners' Lodge.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His new job arrived in time for him to head the local miners against the colliery companies during the General Strike.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] When the strike started on 3 May 1926, Bevan soon emerged as one of the leaders of the South Wales miners.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The miners remained on strike for six months.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was largely responsible for the distribution of strike pay in Tredegar and the formation of the Council of Action, an organisation that helped to raise money and provide food for the miners.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1928, Bevan won a seat on Monmouthshire County Council in the Tredegar Central Division.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He lost the seat in 1931, but regained it in 1932 before deciding against seeking re-election in 1934.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] With his success in 1928, he was picked as the Labour Party candidate for Ebbw Vale (displacing the sitting MP Evan Davies), and easily held the seat at the 1929 General Election.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan gained more than twice the votes of Liberal candidate William Griffiths, receiving 20,000 votes to Griffiths' 8,000.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In keeping with his background, Bevan described his initial thoughts on the House of Commons as a shrine to "the most conservative of all religions – ancestor worship".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In Parliament, he became noticed as a harsh critic of those he felt opposed the working man and woman.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His targets included the Conservative Winston Churchill and the Liberal David Lloyd George, as well as Ramsay MacDonald and Margaret Bondfield from his own Labour party (he targeted the latter for her unwillingness to increase unemployment benefits).
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He had solid support from his constituency, being one of the few Labour MPs to be unopposed in the 1931 General Election, and this support grew through the 1930s and the period of the Great Depression.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Soon after Bevan entered Parliament, he was briefly attracted to Smethwick Labour MP Oswald Mosley's arguments, becoming one of the 17 signatories of the Mosley Memorandum in the context of the MacDonald government's repeated economic crises, including the doubling of unemployment levels.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In January 1931, Bevan wrote a letter to the government on behalf of the Mosley group, raising concerns over its "failure to deal with unemployment".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Mosley broke from the Labour Party in early 1931 to form the New Party, but Bevan refused to defect and instead announced that he had no intention of leaving the Labour Party.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] By 1932, Mosley's New Party had migrated from the left over to the far-right of British politics and was rebranded as the British Union of Fascists.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan's past association with Mosley would be used against him in subsequent years by his political rivals.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He married fellow Socialist MP Jennie Lee in 1934, after they met in London.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Described as "more left-wing than Nye", Lee became a considerable influence on Bevan's political career.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] They were early supporters of the socialists in the Spanish Civil War, and Bevan visited the country in 1938.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1936 he joined the board of the new socialist newspaper *Tribune*.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His agitations for a united socialist front of all parties of the left (including the Communist Party of Great Britain) led to his expulsion from the Labour Party from March to November 1939 (along with Stafford Cripps, C.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan and Cripps had previously been threatened with disciplinary action by the party for sharing a stage with a Communist speaker, and all party members were threatened with expulsion if they were associated with the Popular Front.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan and another expelled MP, George Strauss, appealed against the decision.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was readmitted to the party on 20 December 1939, after agreeing "to refrain from conducting or taking part in campaigns in opposition to the declared policy of the Party".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The Labour conference voted to drop its opposition to rearmament.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] By March 1938, Bevan was writing in *Tribune* that Churchill's warnings about German intentions for Czechoslovakia were "a diapason of majestic harmony" compared to Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain's "thin, listless trickle".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan now called unsuccessfully for a Popular Front coalition against fascism under the leadership of the Labour Party, including even anti-fascist Tories.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] When the government introduced voluntary national service in December 1938, Bevan argued that Labour should demand the nationalisation of the armaments industry, support the democratic government of Spain and sign an Anglo-Soviet pact in return for its support.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] When Labour supported the government's scheme with no such conditions, Bevan denounced Labour for imploring the people on recruiting platforms to put themselves under the leadership of their opponents.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The Military Training Act 1939 reintroduced conscription six months later, and Bevan joined the rest of the Labour Party in opposing it, calling it "the complete abandonment of any hope of a successful struggle against the weight of wealth in Great Britain".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He emphasised that the government had no arguments to persuade young men to fight "except merely in another squalid attempt to defend themselves against the redistribution of international swag".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In August 1939 came the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact, a non-aggression pact between the Nazi and Soviet governments that shocked democratic governments around the world.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In Parliament, Bevan argued that this was the logical outcome of the government's foreign policy.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He wanted the war to be not just a fight against fascism but a war for socialism.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was relieved that the country had united against Nazi Germany in the fight against fascism to provide a common enemy away from the working class.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He was a strong critic of Chamberlain, arguing that his old rival Winston Churchill should become prime minister.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] During the Second World War he was one of the main leaders of the left in the Commons, opposing the wartime Coalition government.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan opposed the heavy censorship imposed on radio and newspapers and wartime Defence Regulation 18B, which gave the Home Secretary the powers to intern citizens.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan called for the nationalisation of the coal industry and advocated the opening of a Second Front in Western Europe to help the Soviet Union in its fight with Germany.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In one of his most noted speeches made against Churchill, he railed that the prime minister "wins debate after debate and loses battle after battle".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Churchill would later label Bevan "a squalid nuisance".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Churchill was a frequent target of Bevan's, who already held a dislike of him following his intervention in the Tonypandy riots and the 1926 United Kingdom general strike which Bevan considered heavy handed.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan believed that the key to the war was the involvement of the USSR and considered Churchill too focused on the intervention of the United States.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan also feared that allowing Churchill to continue unopposed and unchallenged in Parliament during the war would leave him almost unbeatable for the Labour Party in future elections.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Historian Max Hastings described Bevan's role in Parliament during the war as "his figures were accurate but his scorn was at odds with the spirit of the moment—full of gratitude, as was the prime minister".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His fierce opposition made him unpopular with some portions of the public at the time; his wife later described how the couple would frequently receive parcels filled with excrement at their home.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was critical of the leadership of the British Army, which he felt was class bound and inflexible.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] After General Neil Ritchie's retreat across Cyrenaica early in 1942 and his disastrous defeat by General Erwin Rommel at Gazala, Bevan made one of his most memorable speeches in the Commons in support of a motion of censure against the Churchill government.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Dunbar had been recommended for a commission, but rejected it himself to remain with his unit.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was subject to further disciplinary action in 1944, when he deliberately voted against Labour's stance on new defence regulations.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He also voiced criticism of trade union leaders, which drew complaints from both the Miners' Federation and the Trades Union Congress.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] An administrative committee voted 71 to 60 in favour of retaining Bevan as an MP, although it was announced that party discipline was to be strengthened in future.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He believed that the Second World War would give Britain the opportunity to create "a new society".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He often quoted an 1855 passage from Karl Marx that was published in *The New York Times* in 1865: "The redeeming feature of war is that it puts a nation to the test.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] We enter this campaign at this general election, not merely to get rid of the Tory majority.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The 1945 general election resulted in a landslide victory for the Labour Party, giving it a large enough majority to allow the implementation of the party's manifesto commitments and to introduce a programme of far-reaching social reforms, that were collectively dubbed the "Welfare State".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] These reforms were achieved in the face of great financial difficulty following the war.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The new Prime Minister, Clement Attlee, appointed Bevan as Minister of Health, with a remit that also covered housing.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Thus, the responsibility for instituting a new and comprehensive National Health Service, as well as tackling the country's severe post-war housing shortage, was given to Bevan, the youngest member of Attlee's Cabinet in his first ministerial position at the age of 47.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Although described in *The Times* as "an outstanding back-bench critic" and "one of (Labour's) most brilliant members in debate", his appointment was regarded as a relative surprise, given his previous disciplinary issues.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan had clashed frequently with Attlee during his time as an MP, believing that the Labour leader failed to apply enough pressure on the Tory government during the war.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He had also had disputes with some of Attlee's closest allies, Ernest Bevin and Herbert Morrison, who were appointed Foreign Secretary and Leader of the House respectively.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] However, Attlee commented that Bevan was "starting with me with a clean sheet" following his appointment.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan tested this newfound solidarity early on by arriving to a royal banquet at St James's Palace wearing a navy lounge suit.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He earned a rebuke from Attlee, but Bevan contended that his Welsh mining constituency did not send him to Parliament to "dress up", and he declined to wear formal attire at further Buckingham Palace functions.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The free National Health Service was paid for directly through public money.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan had been inspired by the Tredegar Medical Aid Society in his hometown, where residents would pay a subscription to enable all subscribers and their dependants to have free access to medical services such as nursing or dental care.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] This system proved so popular that 20,000 people supported the organisation during the 1930s.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Having been a member of the Cottage Hospital Management Committee around 1928 and serving as chairman in 1929–30, Bevan had received an insight into the management of health services by local authorities, which proved to be a bedrock of his work in founding the National Health Service.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] On the "appointed day", 5 July 1948, Bevan's National Health Service Act 1946 came into force.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] On the day, Bevan attended a ceremony at the Park Hospital, Trafford (now Trafford General), at which he symbolically received the keys to the hospital.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The scheme was achieved having overcome political opposition from both the Conservative Party and from within his own party.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Confrontation with the British Medical Association (BMA) was led by Charles Hill, who published a letter in the *British Medical Journal* describing Bevan as "a complete and uncontrolled dictator".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Members of the BMA had dubbed him the "Tito of Tonypandy".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] They threatened to derail the National Health Service scheme before it had even begun, as medical practitioners continued to withhold their support just months before the launch of the service.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] At a dinner in late 1955 or early 1956 to celebrate the publication of the Guillebaud Report into NHS costs Bevan remarked to Julian Tudor Hart "ultimately I had to stuff their mouths with gold" about his handling of the consultants.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] This is often quoted as "I stuffed their mouths with gold".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Some 2,688 voluntary and municipal hospitals in England and Wales were nationalised and came under Bevan's supervisory control as Health Minister.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Two of the key elements of Bevan's proposals were this nationalisation of the hospital services and the abolition of the sale and purchase of goodwill by general practitioners.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The former aimed to provide a uniform standard of consultant led care and expertise throughout the country and to replace the patchwork of voluntary and municipal hospitals which existed at that point.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The latter – sale and purchase of goodwill – often placed new entrants to the GP profession under large amounts of debt.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Along with this, the Medical Practices Committee was to oversee the distribution of GP practices – a proposal which the previous Coalition Minister had withdrawn after opposition from the British Medical Association.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Conservative opposition of the National Health Service scheme feared that the sudden access to free health care would be overrun.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In its early stages this proved true, as the service went vastly over budget in its inaugural year, and Attlee was forced to make a radio address to the nation in an attempt to limit the strain on the system.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan countered that the initial overspending was down to years of underinvestment in the British medical system prior to the Second World War: by the start of the 1950s, the early overspending had come to an end.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The removal of the criteria of "working class" from local authority housing provision was seen as a first step, widening access to the council housing that was becoming an ever larger part of the UK housing stock and which made up a majority of new homes built after the war.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Substantial bombing damage, with over 700,000 homes needing repair in London alone, and the continued existence of pre-war slums in many parts of the country made the task of housing reform particularly challenging for Bevan.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Indeed, these factors, exacerbated by post-war restrictions on the availability of building materials and skilled labour, collectively served to limit Bevan's achievements in this area.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was also limited due to his desire for new homes to be bigger and of better quality than the ones they were being built to replace, based on the recommendations of a 1943 report by the Dudley Committee, and a shortage of skilled workers to undertake the work.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] These numbers were reached by lowering the quality standards originally put forward by Bevan, with council houses featuring gardens being largely dropped in favour of tower blocks and flats.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Macmillan was also able to concentrate full-time on the housing crisis, instead of being obliged, like Bevan, to combine his housing portfolio with that for Health (which for Bevan took the higher priority: he once stated tongue-in-cheek that he devoted "five minutes a week to housing").
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] At a party rally in 1948, during a speech, Bevan stated: "That is why no amount of cajolery, and no attempts at ethical or social seduction, can eradicate from my heart a deep burning hatred for the Tory Party that inflicted those bitter experiences on me.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] So far as I am concerned they are lower than vermin.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] They condemned millions of first-class people to semi-starvation." The comment inspired the creation of the Vermin Club by angry Conservatives, who attacked Bevan for years for the metaphor.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Labour Party deputy leader Herbert Morrison complained that Bevan's attack had backfired, for his words "did much more to make the Tories work and vote ... than Conservative Central Office could have done".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] It was later claimed that his words had cost Labour more than two million votes.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1951, with the retirement of Ernest Bevin, Bevan was a leading candidate for Foreign Secretary.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Prime Minister Attlee rejected Bevan in favour of Herbert Morrison because he distrusted Bevan's personality.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In his biography of Bevan, John Campbell wrote: "Bevan's impetuous temperament, undiplomatic tone and reputation as an extreme left-winger combined to make the Foreign Office seem the last place a prudent Prime Minister would think of putting him at any time.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan was instead appointed Minister of Labour in January 1951 in place of George Isaacs.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The move was seen by some as a sideways or backwards step, although a potential rearmament programme was expected to make the post of future importance.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] During his tenure, Bevan helped to secure a deal for railwaymen which provided them with a significant pay increase.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] However, three months after his appointment, Hugh Gaitskell introduced a proposal of prescription charges for dental care and spectacles—created to save a potential £25m to meet the financial demands imposed by the Korean War.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] An infuriated Bevan stated that he would never be a member of a government that imposed charges on the National Health Service.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] The Labour MP David Marquand has stated that the savings were introduced by Gaitskell simply to "impose his will" upon Bevan who he saw as a political rival.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan resigned from his position two weeks later, stating both the proposed changes and the increase in military expenditure that necessitated the need for such proposals.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Two other ministers, John Freeman and Harold Wilson, resigned at the same time.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan received unanimous support for his actions from his local Labour constituency leaders.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Later the same year, the Labour Party were defeated at the general election.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] After Bevan left the Health ministry in 1951 he could never regain his level of success and feuded with fellow Labour leaders, using his strong political base as a weapon.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Morgan says: "Bevan alone kept the flag of left-wing socialism aloft throughout—which gave him a matchless authority amongst the constituency parties and in party conference".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Bevan's last decade saw his political position weaken year by year as he failed to find a winning issue that would make use of his skills.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In 1952 Bevan published *In Place of Fear*, "the most widely read socialist book" of the period, according to a highly critical right-wing Labour MP Anthony Crosland.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] According to *The Times Literary Supplement*, the book was a "dithyramb with meanderings into the many side-tracks of Mr Bevan's private and public experience".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In March 1952, a poorly prepared Bevan came off the worse in an evening Commons debate on health with Conservative backbencher Iain Macleod, whose performance led Churchill to appoint him as Minister of Health some six weeks after the debate.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Out of office, Bevan soon exacerbated the split within the Labour Party between the right and the left which weakened the party in the 1950s.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] For the next five years, he was the leader of the left wing of the Labour Party, who became known as Bevanites.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] They criticised the right-wing "Gaitskellites" high defence expenditure (especially for nuclear weapons), called for better relations with the Soviet Union, and opposed the party leader, Clement Attlee, on most issues.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] According to Richard Crossman, Bevan hated "the in-fighting which you have to do in politics....
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He wasn't cut out to be a leader, he was cut out to be a prophet".
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In April 1954, Bevan resigned from the Shadow Cabinet, having been rebuked by Attlee after accusing the Labour leader of surrendering to American pressure over a proposed multi-national defence organisation in Asia and the Pacific.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] He later said that he had resigned his position to "call attention to the fact that their movement was in grave crisis", and stated his belief that he would have been party chairman by the following year if he had remained.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In July of the same year, Bevan announced his intention to stand for election as the Treasurer of the Labour Party against Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] His nomination received a severe blow on the same day it was announced, when two unions that traditionally sided with the left, the National Union of Mineworkers and the Amalgamated Engineering Union, pledged their support for his opponent.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] Although unsuccessful in his bid, he did celebrate 25 years as the MP for Ebbw Vale.
[src:national-health-service/aneurin-bevan-p01] In March 1955, when Britain was preparing for Operation Grapple, the testing of its first hydrogen bomb, Bevan led a revolt of 57 Labour MPs and abstained on a key vote.
